<HEADLINE> US Consumer Prices Up by 0.1 Percent in April </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, May 15 (Xinhua) -- The consumer prices in the U.S.
increased by a small 0.1 percent in April resulting from declining
energy and food costs, U.S. Labor Department reported today.
</P>
<P>
The tiny rise in the U.S. Consumer Price Index (CPI) held the
inflation rate to a seasonally adjusted annual rate of just 1.5
percent for the first four months of the year.
</P>
<P>
Much of the inflation relief has come in the volatile food and
energy sectors, where prices are unwinding from earlier increases.
</P>
<P>
The report said that energy prices fell by 1.5 percent in April
following a 1.7 percent drop in March. Food prices also declined
by 0.2 percent with declines in fruit and vegetables, cereal and
dairy products offsetting increases in meat, poultry, fish and
eggs.
</P>
<P>
Excluding food and energy, the so-called core prices rose a
moderate 0.3 percent in April, the largest since September. The
core prices in the U.S. increased at the annual rate of 2.7
percent in the first four months of this year.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. Federal Reserve (Fed) policy-makers will meet on next
Tuesday to consider if another increase of interest rate is needed
to check the inflation.
</P>
<P>
Some economists expect the central bank will wait to see if
recent signs of economic slowing continue, while others expect
another rate rise as insurance to make sure growth slows to a
non-inflationary pace.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Fed raised the short-term interest rate by a quarter of a
percentage point on March 25, the first increase in two years.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
