<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UK Inflation Rate Drops to 2.4 pct in April </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, May 15 (Xinhua) -- Britain's headline annual inflation
fell to 2.4 percent last month from 2.6 percent in March as retail
prices rose only 0.6 percent in the month, according to figures
released today by the Office for National Statistics (ONS).
</P>
<P>
The underlying annual inflation rate, which excludes mortgage
interest payments and which the government has set as a target at
2.5 percent or less, also showed a fall from 2.7 percent in March
to 2.5 percent, which surprised City experts.
</P>
<P>
This was the lowest annual figure since November 1994 when
underlying inflation was at 2.3 percent and means that the former
Conservative government met its target in its last month in power
as it was ousted from office when Labor leader Tony Blair won a
landslide victory in the May 1 election.
</P>
<P>
The ONS said that the falls were largely due to a drop in
motoring costs, with prices for vehicles, petrol and oil all
falling in April.
</P>
<P>
Analysts believed that the short term outlook of inflation
remains stable as the strength of the pound is keeping a lid on
prices.  
</P>
</TEXT>
