<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Huaneng Power International Issues Convertible Notes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, May 15 (Xinhua) -- China's Huaneng Power International
issued 200 million US dollars of 7-year notes on Wednesday,
convertible into the company's Overseas Shares or American
Depositary Shares (ADS).
</P>
<P>
The issue marks the first time a Chinese company has issued
SEC-registered convertible bonds with JP Morgan as lead manager
for the transaction.
</P>
<P>
The 1.75% notes pay interest semi-annually and are convertible
at 29.20 US dollars per ADS, an 18% premium to the closing price
of 24.75 US dollars on 13 May, according to a press release
issued by JP Morgan here today.
</P>
<P>
The notes are callable at par from 21 May 2000 provided the ADS
price is at least 130% of the conversion price for 30 consecutive
trading days.
</P>
<P>
Investors have the right to put the notes on 21 May 2002 at
price that would produce a yield of 6.66%, or 10 basis points over
comparable five-year US Treasury notes as of noon London time on
14 May.
</P>
<P>
The notes were offered simultaneously in the North American,
European, and Asian markets and will be listed on the New York
Stock Exchange and Luxembourg Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
The Beijing-based Huaneng Power International is the largest
publicly listed independent power producer in Asia, with an
operating capacity of 3500 MW. 
</P>
</TEXT>
