<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Technology Teaching in UK Needs "Money Boost" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, May 15 (Xinhua) -- Britain's schools need heavy input
for technology teaching if the country's future as a highly
competitive and innovative nation is not to be jeopardized,
according to a report published today by the Engineering Council.
</P>
<P>
The report, based on a survey of 344 state secondary schools by
Brunel University, found that the teaching of technology in
secondary schools is "bedevilled by underfunding".
</P>
<P>
According to the report, In 1994-1995, the average technology
departmental grant was 5.86 pounds (9.37 US dollars) per pupil,
well below the 9.30 pounds (14.88 US dollars) recommended by the
Design and Technology Association.
</P>
<P>
The following year, nearly two-fifths of the country's
technology departments suffered a cut in grant funding which was
bound to affect on the teaching quality of technology.
</P>
<P>
Because schools did not have enough money to teach technology
as prescribed by the national curriculum. At several schools,
facilities were inadequate.
</P>
<P>
In over a fifth of schools, the specialized workshops were too
small and there was an overspill into ordinary class rooms, the
report said.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, the schools could not even hire properly qualified
staff. In a fifth of specialist technology colleges, the equipment
existed, but not the teachers trained to use it.
</P>
<P>
Incredibly, in nearly half of all schools, technology
departments did not have a full-time technician.
</P>
<P>
The report pointed out that "a rolling program of 100 million
pounds (160 million US dollars) per year for 10 years" is required
to provide the necessary capital investment.
</P>
<P>
There should also be "a relatively modest" 10 million pounds
(16 million US dollars) annual investment to bring recurrent
funding up to an "acceptable level", it added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
