<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Netanyahu Optimistic About Renewing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, May 15 (Xinhua) -- Despite the lack of breakthrough
from U.S. peace envoy Dennis Ross' mediation, Israeli Prime
Minister Binyamin Netanyahu still voiced optimism about renewing
the stalled Israeli-Palestinian peace talks.
</P>
<P>
After meeting with Ross this morning, Netanyahu told his
coalition executives at a meeting that Ross' mission created the
basis for more talks despite the failure of the Wednesday night
meeting between Israeli and Palestinian officials to break the ice.
</P>
<P>
The Wednesday meeting, the first between Israeli and
Palestinian negotiators since the Har Homa construction, was held
at the Herzliya residence of U.S. Ambassador Matin Indyk and
attended by Israeli Defense Minister Yitzhak Mordechai, senior
Palestinian negotiator Saeb Erekat and other officials.
</P>
<P>
Erekat said no results were achieved at the meeting, which he
described as only a dialog and not formal negotiations. He said
Israel had rejected the Palestinian demand that Israel should
first freeze settlement activities, including the Har Homa
project, before resuming formal talks.
</P>
<P>
Despite the current stalemate in the peace process, Netanyahu
expressed the hope that the Knesset's summer session would
witness the renewal of peace talks with the Palestinian National
Authority (PNA). He stressed that the talks had to be renewed
because they are in the interests of both sides.
</P>
<P>
In contrast, Erekat painted a bleak picture of the prospects
for renewing the peace process. In an interview with Israel Radio,
he said Israel was no longer a peace partner to the Palestinian
side, because of its continued expansion of settlements and
confiscation of Palestinian land.
</P>
<P>
Erekat described Ross' mission as a failure which resulted
from Israel's intransgiency on the settlement issue. He urged
the U.S. government to stand firm against Israel's policies of
continuing expanding settlements.
</P>
<P>
He also refuted Israel's charges against PNA President Yasser
Arafat for giving the green light to terrorist attacks against
Israel, saying Arafat "has made it very clear that he would not
tolerate anyone who may even think of inflicting harm or violence
against Israelis."
</P>
<P>
By blaming Arafat for giving the green light to terrorism,
Israel is citing the PNA's promise to launch a long-term fight
against terrorism as a precondition for renewing the peace talks.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Ross held talks with Israeli President Ezer Weizman
this afternoon and is scheduled to meet with Arafat in Gaza late
today. He was trying to arrange another meeting between Israeli
and Palestinian security officials to discuss security cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Ross, who arrived here last Wednesday, is expected to
travel home Friday to report to President Bill Clinton and
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright on his current mission.
</P>
</TEXT>
