<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cohen Presents U.S. Defense Plan to Congress </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, May 15 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Defense Secretary William
Cohen today presented leaders of Congress the Quadrennial Defense
Review (QDR), a new plan for U.S. military strategy.
</P>
<P>
The QDR, which is due to be made public on Monday, aims at
force cuts and arms modernization into the next century.
</P>
<P>
Cohen had called for new base closings and shrinking costly jet
fighter programs. Reports say that the QDR would cut only some
60,000 troops from the 1.4 million-member military.
</P>
<P>
Dozens of senior lawmakers and staffers from four key security
and appropriations committees of the House and Senate gathered at
Cohen's office in the Pentagon and attended the close-door
briefing by Cohen.
</P>
<P>
The QDR, which is the most important defense strategy document
mapped out by the Pentagon after the end of the Cold War,
basically has not changed much the strategic goal of the United
States: it should be capable of winning two regional wars
simultaneously.
</P>
<P>
The QDR, Cohen said earlier this month, is a compromise to face
the realities of growing demands on the military such as fighting
wars, keeping the peace and performing humanitarian duties along
with saving save money to spend on needed arms modernization.
</P>
<P>
He emphasized the end of the Cold War had not ended
international threats to U.S. security and that more domestic
military bases must be shut to save money for new high-tech
weapons. 
</P>
</TEXT>
