<HEADLINE> German Tax Revenue Shortfall Estimated at 18 Billion Marks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, May 15 (Xinhua) -- Tax revenues by federal, state and
community governments in Germany this year will be 18 billion
German marks (10.65 billion U.S. dollars) lower than earlier
estimated, a government-appointed tax estimate group announced
today.
</P>
<P>
According to the latest projections, federal taxes for this
year were expected to be 9.1 billion marks lower than earlier
expected, those of the country's 16 states would be 6.9 billion
lower, and the community governments would also expected 1.8
billion marks less tax revenues than before.
</P>
<P>
German Finance Minister Theo Waigel attributed the huge
shortfall to the sluggish German economy and the record high
unemployment. He was scheduled to make a statement later Thursday
to say what the government will undertake to try to close the
financial gaps.
</P>
<P>
The tax projections Thursday was made by the so-called "Working
Group for Tax Estimates", which is comprised of experts from
federal, state and community governments as well as officials from
the central bank known as Bundesbank, the Federal Statistics
Office and the independent economic research institutes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
