<HEADLINE> Turkey Lauds NATO-Russia Agreement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, May 15 (Xinhua) -- Turkey today lauded the agreement
reached between Russia and the North Atlantic Treaty Organization
(NATO), on forging a new bilateral relationship following the cold
war.
</P>
<P>
A statement issued by the Turkish Foreign Ministry said NATO
Secretary General Janvier Solana and Russian Foreign Minister
Yevgeny Primakov had played "a constructive role" in the two-day
talks between May 13 and 14.
</P>
<P>
The just-concluded agreement is designed to frame the future
relations between Russian and the organization, while reducing the
worry of the Russian Federation on the eastward expansion of the
NATO.
</P>
<P>
With this development, "an important step" has been taken
towards Europe's new security structure and "concrete improvement"
has been made for the Russian Federation to play its part in
Europe in the next century, stressed the statement.
</P>
<P>
It also said that Turkey, a NATO member for 45 years, will
contribute to the implementation of the document expected to be
signed in Paris, France, on May 27.
</P>
<P>
The 16-page agreement is called the Founding Act on Mutual
Relations, Cooperation and Security between the NATO and
Russia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
