<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ireland to Have General Election on June 6 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, May 15 (Xinhua) -- Irish Prime Minister John Bruton
announced in Dublin today that he is to dissolve the Irish
parliament and call an early general election on June 6, five
months before the November deadline.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the Irish parliament early today, Bruton said that
he intended to go to Irish President Mary Robinson to request her
permission to dissolve the country's 27th parliament, according to
press reports from Dublin.
</P>
<P>
Bruton, who came to power in late 1994 when the previous
government collapsed because of a row over legal appointments,
said that the current three-party coalition, including Fine Gael
party, Labor Party and the Democratic Left, should fight off the
opposition on the coalition's record of creating jobs and
prosperity.
</P>
<P>
"Promises are one thing. Performance is another. Jobs are the
centerpiece of this government. We want to halve unemployment and
add 1,000 jobs each week over the next five years just as we have
over the last two years," he said.
</P>
<P>
Opinion polls indicate that the popularity of the ruling
coalition has been fading fast in the wake of revelations that an
Irish tycoon, Ben Dunne, paid millions of pounds to politicians
from all parties.
</P>
<P>
Irish elections are held under a proportional representation
system. A poll last week gave the main opposition Fianna Fail
party 43 per cent of votes with the Progressive Democrats taking
eight. For the coalition, Fine Gael was on 26 percent, Labour 12
and Democratic Left two.
</P>
<P>
Irish political commentators said that unemployment, law and
order and the Northern Ireland peace process are expected to
dominate the election campaign. 
</P>
</TEXT>
