<HEADLINE> 87 PKK Rebels Killed in Cross-Border Operations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, May 15 (Xinhua) -- Eighty-seven rebels of the outlawed
Kurdish Workers' Party (PKK) have been killed since the
50,000-strong Turkish troops crossed the border into northern Iraq
Wednesday in a bid to wipe out the PKK militants based in the
region, a military statement said here today.
</P>
<P>
The statement issued by the office of the General Staff said
that the PKK rebels were killed along the Sirnak and Hakkari
border lines when they fleed the heavy clashes with Iraq's
Kurdistan Democratic Party (KDP) forces in northern Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Turkish private Show TV reported this evening that the
Turkish security forces have entered into 40 kilometers of
northern Iraq since Turkey launched a large-scale cross-border
military operations Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The statement also said that one soldier of the Turkish
security forces died and four others were wounded in the clashes
with the PKK rebels in northern Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The PKK militants are still fighting with the KDP forces in
the region, said the statement.
</P>
<P>
Sermat Atacanli, deputy spokesman of the Turkish Foreign
Ministry, said Wednesday that the Turkish government troops
launched the cross-border military operations following a call
for aid by KDP Chairman Mesud Barzani.
</P>
<P>
The PKK has been fighting a separatist war for autonomy in
southeastern Turkey since August 1984. Its armed wing, based in
northern Iraq, has been waging hit-and-run battles against the
government forces. 
</P>
</TEXT>
