<HEADLINE> World Silver Supply Sets to Tighten, Says Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, May 15 (Xinhua) -- World silver supply is not keeping
pace with demand and the supply gap sets to widen, according to
the latest World Silver Survey published Wednesday by the
London-based Gold Fields Mineral Services consultancy.
</P>
<P>
The survey, sponsored by 28 silver miners, refiners,
fabricators and bullion banks from nine countries, said that world
silver market was moving in the direction of a genuine tightening
of supply and 24,800 tons of silver were drawn from stocks
between 1991 and the end of 1996 due to short of supply.
</P>
<P>
It suggested that the gap between fabrication demand and the
combined total of supply from mine production and scrap widened to
nearly 5,000 tons last year although it was below the record
5,600 tons in 1993.
</P>
<P>
The report warned that identifiable silver stocks would be
eliminated if the gap between supply and demand continued at the
same level for another four years.
</P>
<P>
There would be a point at which the fall in stocks began to
make a noticeable difference to the availability of silver to the
market, it pointed out.
</P>
<P>
"If the existing holders of the remaining stocks of bullion
should choose to maintain rather than to dispose of their
holdings, the only way that the market will achieve a balance is
via a significant increase in the silver price," the report added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
