<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe Denies Manufacturing Landmines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, May 15 (Xinhua) -- The Zimbabwe government today
officially dispelled the rumour that it manufactures
anti-personnel landmines, saying it had not done so since
independence in 1980.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwe's Defence Minister Moven Mahachi said that it was not
Zimbabwe's policy to either manufacture or keep the devices in
the country.
</P>
<P>
In fact, he said, tenders would soon be invited for the
removal of landmines from the country's north-eastern border.
</P>
<P>
He said, ''you may be aware that Zimbabwe has been accused of
manufacturing anti-personnel mines.''
</P>
<P>
''To restore our image which has been maliciously tarnished, I
am proud to announce the following policy position -- Zimbabwe
has not manufactured anti-personnel mines since 1980,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
Various groups, including the human rights body, British-based
Human Rights Watch, has in the past challenged the government to
clarify a situation where it has been seen to be manufacturing
and exporting landmines.
</P>
<P>
Mahachi also dispelled assertions that his government had
exported landmines to Sudan, for use by rebels.
</P>
<P>
The government, he said, did not have the technology or
capacity to manufacture the landmines, nor did it intend to
acquire such technology in future.
</P>
<P>
The Zimbabwe government has now secured a 11.4 million US
dollars loan from the European Union for removing about one
million anti-personnel mines in northeastern Zimbabwe. enditem

