<HEADLINE> Waigel: Germany's Chances to Join Euro Unchanged </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, May 15 (Xinhua) -- German Finance Minister Theo Waigel
insisted today that Germany's chances to join the single European
currency remain unchanged, despite projections issued today
pointing to a huge shortfall in the government's 1997 tax
revenues.
</P>
<P>
An estimated shortfall of 18 billion German marks (10.6 billion
U.S. dollars) -- caused mainly by record unemployment and a
sluggish economy -- would have no effect on Germany's prospects to
join the single currency known as the Euro, Waigel said.
</P>
<P>
He also insisted that there should be no weakening of the tough
financial targets set by the European Union Maastricht treaty for
Euro membership.
</P>
<P>
But economists in Frankfurt said Bonn was unlikely now to meet
the Maastricht criteria, meant to ensure that the Euro will be as
strong as the German mark.
</P>
<P>
With high unemployment pushing up social security spendings,
German government is now facing urgent financial measures to bring
its budget deficit under three percent of gross domestic product
(GDP), as required by the Euro criteria.
</P>
<P>
The decision on which states are to qualify for the Euro in the
first wave on January 1, 1999 will be made early in 1998, based on
countries' full economic data of 1997. 
</P>
</TEXT>
