<HEADLINE> Ethiopia, Japan Sign Air Service Accord </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, May 15 (xinhua) -- Ethiopia and Japan today
signed exchange of notes for the implementation of a bilateral
air service agreement signed by Ethiopian Vice-Foreign Minister
Tekeda Alemu and Japanese Ambassador to Ethiopia Yasuhiro Hamada.
</P>
<P>
Alemu said the agreement will help strengthen the bilateral
trade and economic ties, while Hamada said it will contribute to
Asian-African economic cooperation, thereby strengthening and
developing social and cultural ties.
</P>
<P>
The bilateral air service agreement, signed in March, 1996,
enabled the Ethiopian Airlines to start scheduled flights to
Japan this year and facilitated the Japanese Airlines to start
similar operations to Ethiopia.
</P>
<P>
The agreement indicated the strengthening of air links between
east Africa and the Far East.
</P>
<P>
The Ethiopian Airlines is now flying to Beijing, China via New
Delhi, India fortnightly and to Bangkok, Thailand twice a week.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Hamada on Wednesday donated to the Addis Ababa
Regional Administration waste some disposal equipment worth five
million U.S. Dollars, including 10 detachable container trucks,
100 containers, 16 dump trucks, 10 compactor trucks and one water
jet cleaner with spare parts. 
