<DOCNO> XIE19970516.0034 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-15 18:51 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Middle East Business Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, May 15 (Xinhua) -- The following are business briefs
from Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
AMMAN -- Jordan's contracting industry is in recession, Jordan
Times today quoted the Jordan Contractors Association (JCA)
president Wael Touqan as saying.
</P>
<P>
Only 500 out of 1,200 JCA members are now employed, said the
president.
</P>
<P>
Private and major public share-holding companies are tendering
projects requiring the participation of foreign companies and
firms not involved in the contractor business, he added.
</P>
<P>
The contracting sector has employed 13 percent of the
country's workforce and makes up 10 percent of Jordan's gross
national product, Touqan said.
</P>
<P>
NICOSIA -- Cyprus is expected to import about 700 to 760
thousand tonnes of grain in the year to April 30, 1998.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus Grain Commission Manager Charalambos Archimandrites
said today that Cyprus will import about 70 to 80 thousand
tonnes of wheat, 450 to 500 thousand tonnes of barley and 180
thousand tonnes of maize.
</P>
<P>
Archimandrites noted that the countries from which the grain
will be imported and the imports' financial cost are not yet
known.
</P>
<P>
"It depends on the tenders, and then the prices," he added.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- The private sector now controls nearly 40 percent of
Egypt's annual 1.8-million-tonne sugar market, up from less than
10 percent in 1990, according to the May 1997 issue of Egypt's
Business Monthly magazine.
</P>
<P>
This is the result of the government's privatization drive
which encouraged the private sectors to play a more active role
in the trade, the magazine said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, private firms are now entirely responsible for
importing 700,000 tonnes of sugar Egypt needs to make up for its
production deficit each year.
</P>
<P>
The Sugar and Integrated Industries Company (SIIC), an
affiliate of the Food Industries Holding Co., has controlled the
sugar market ever since President Gamal Abdel Nasser nationalized
the holdings of sugar-magnate Abu Pasha.
</P>
<P>
Sugar is considered Egypt's second most sensitive commodity
after wheat. Contrary to a popular belief, Egyptians' sugar
consumption lags behind that of developed nations.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Britain has agreed with Egypt with its participation
in developing the Abu Tartour Phosphate Scheme Mines, in the west
of the Nile River, towards stepping up production, reducing
costs of opening up the ore.
</P>
<P>
This was announced Wednesday by Egyptian Minister of Industry
and Mineral Resources Sulaiman Reda after a meeting with a
British delegation of mining industry experts in Cairo.
</P>
<P>
Reda said that the British side agreed on extending technical
assistance in training phosphate mine workers.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, Britain had promised to offer aid in search for
subscribers to the Scheme in building the Abu Tartour Phosphate
Chemical Complex when phosphoric acid from the Abu Tartour
Phosphate Mines ore can be successfully produced at the Abu Zaabal
Fertilizers Plant near Cairo. 
</P>
