<HEADLINE> Turkey Wants to Resume Trade With Iraq, Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, May 15 (Xinhua) -- Turkey said today that it was
considering resuming trade with the sanction-ridden Iraq, but
under the U.N. convention.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a press conference here, Energy Minister Recai
Kutan said that the government was working out ways of
circumventing the U.N. trade embargo imposed on Baghdad following
the Iraqi invasion of Kuwait in 1990.
</P>
<P>
Taking Jordan as an example, Kutan said the kingdom was taking
advantage of Article 50 of the U.N. Convention, which sets terms
for one country to trade with another that is under sanction.
</P>
<P>
Jordan has simply informed the U.N. under the article and is
going ahead with trade with Iraq, the minister said, indicating
that Turkey could also resume its trade with Baghdad in the same
way.
</P>
<P>
During his recent trip to Baghdad, Kutan signed a oil and
natural gas deal with Iraqi Oil Minister Amir Muhammad Rasheed,
which is termed as an important step in the two countries'
trade ties.
</P>
<P>
While meeting with the Iraqi minister, Kutan called the
trade embargo on Iraq "meaningless and unjust."
</P>
<P>
Turkey has reportedly suffered an estimated economic loss of
around 30 billion U.S. dollars as a result of the U.N. trade
sanctions on Baghdad.
</P>
<P>
Months ago, Turkey had tried to ask for permission from
the United Nations to trade with Iraq, but received a reply
that this would be considered only after outcome of the
oil-for-food agreement had been assessed.
</P>
<P>
To relieve the suffering of the Iraqis, the United Nations
has allowed Iraq to sell two-billion-U.S. dollar worth of oil
in order to buy badly needed food and medicine in the
sanction-stricken country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
