<HEADLINE> Cypriot Government Supports U.N.-Sponsored </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, May 15 (Xinhua) -- The Cypriot government has voiced
its support to an upcoming bicommunal concert, an event it hopes
will carry a message of hope to the young people of Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters today after a meeting of the Council of
Ministers, Government Spokesman Manolis Christofides said "we
look forward to the concert with the wish that it will open a
window of hope."
</P>
<P>
The United Nations has organized a concert for Greek and
Turkish Cypriots, in a bid to build bridges between the two
communities who are kept apart since Turkey sent troops and took
control of the northern third of the island in 1974.
</P>
<P>
Greek pop star Sakis Rouvas, along with Turkish singer Burak
Kut will perform during the Monday night's concert.
</P>
<P>
A total of 6,000 tickets - 3,000 for each side - are being
distributed free of charge, for the concert will take place on a
vacant football court in the buffer zone in Nicosia.
</P>
<P>
Noting that the young generation is the "golden hope" for all
nations, Christofides stressed that the young people of Cyprus
"have been kept apart for decades against nature and their own
interest."
</P>
<P>
"Greek and Turkish Cypriots will come to the concert proud of
their descent and to declare they want peace and peaceful
coexistence," the spokesman added.
</P>
<P>
He thanked both Rouvas and Kut for their responding to the
U.N. invitation, stressing that they will contribute to the
creation of an environment of friendship between the young
people of Cyprus, through the universal language of music and
songs.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said the Cypriot government encourages young
people to participate in the event and called upon political
parties to use this opportunity to "send the message that the
youth of Cyprus can work and live together peacefully."
</P>
<P>
He expressed the hope that "other similar events will follow,
bringing the people of Cyprus to live and create together."
</P>
<P>
It was reported that the event has met opposition from
certain organizations in both sides, but the U.N. has said it
will deploy some 400 security personnel to the concert, to
guarantee the safety of all those present. 
</P>
