<DOCNO> XIE19970516.0042 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gold Market Trend Depend On EMU, Says GFMS </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, May 15 (Xinhua) -- The decline in investment interest
in gold last year could be coming to an end, according to an
annual report published here recently.
</P>
<P>
The first quarter of this year is showing some of the
characteristics which led to the bull market of 1993, despite the
spirit of pervading gloom which surrounded gold at the end of last
year, Gold Fields Mineral Services (GFMS) said in the report.
</P>
<P>
The parallels are similar, with a depressed price and record
levels of demand from Asian gold markets.
</P>
<P>
There was clearly a circular relationship between the falling
price and the lack of investment interest, with the perception of
falling prices encouraging short selling and the resulting sale of
borrowed gold pushing the price down further, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Yet the gold price this year has so far not been outstanding.
At the close of trading on 12 May, gold was 348.2 US dollars per
ounce, trailing behind last year's low of 367.4 US dollars.
</P>
<P>
"We might begin to see the message get through to investors as
some start to believe that there is a reason for prices to rise,"
said Stewart Murray, chief executive of GFMS.
</P>
<P>
"This will lead others to come in and push prices higher
again," he added.
</P>
<P>
It is believed that the stock market was the main reason for
poor gold prices last year. The market's buoyancy, particularly in
the US, where one expects most gold investment to stem from, meant
investors stayed away from gold.
</P>
<P>
The continued fall of the price during the first quarter of
this year triggered a tremendous physical reaction in the Asian
markets, which certainly prevented the price from sliding any
further, and may even have had a big enough impact on sentiment to
encourage some short covering, the report pointed out.
</P>
<P>
For the future, the report said:"The trend in the gold market
may depend to quite an extent on the market's perception of the
probability of success or otherwise of European Monetary Union."
</P>
<P>
"Much remains to be decided about gold's role in this process
and there is still no clear consensus on whether gold will benefit
or suffer from it," it added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
