<HEADLINE> US Industrial Production Unchanged in April </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, May 15 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. industrial production
was unchanged in April after a downward-revised increase of 0.6
percent in March, the U.S. Federal Reserve (Fed) reported today.
</P>
<P>
The report said that the production was held back by auto
strikes, which caused a 6.4 percent drop in production of autos,
trucks and parts.
</P>
<P>
Excluding the decline in the production of motor vehicles and
parts, the index of U.S. industrial production rose 0.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
The output of durable goods, items expected to last for more
than three years, fell 3.5 percent in the month, mainly resulting
from the big decline of automotives.
</P>
<P>
The output of nondurable goods advanced by 0.2 percent boosted
by increase in the production of energy products.
</P>
<P>
Manufacturing output overall slipped by 0.2 percent, the first
drop in 13 months. Mining, which includes oil drilling, fell by
0.5 percent. However, cold, rainy weather helped boost output at
utilities by 2 percent.
</P>
<P>
The changes left American industry operating at 83.4 percent of
its capacity, down from 83.7 percent in March. It was the lowest
operating rate in three months and an indication consumer demand
isn't creating inflationary bottlenecks in the production
pipeline. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
