<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ECOSOC Projects 4.3 Pct Growth in Western Asia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, May 15 (Xinhua) -- The economy in western Asia
will grow 4.3 percent in 1997, lower than the 4.8 percent growth
for 1996 but much higher than the 2.2 percent growth achieved in
1995, according to a survey of the UN Economic and Social Council
(ECOSOC).
</P>
<P>
The survey showed that the real per capita gross domestic
product (GDP) in the region consisting of 13 countries will
average 2.1 percent this year.
</P>
<P>
The economic outlook for the region will mainly depend on the
international prices of oil, the implementation of economic
reforms of the countries in the region, the development in the
Middle East peace process and Iraq's return to the international
oil market and lifting of the sanctions on Iraq, according to the
survey.
</P>
<P>
In reviewing the overall economic performance in 1996, the
survey noted that the region's GDP, in nominal terms and excluding
Iraq, totaled 353.3 billion dollars, up by 10.1 percent from the
320.8 billion dollars in 1995. Its per capita nominal GDP was
estimated at 2,828 dollars in 1996, compared with 2,638 dollars in
the previous year.
</P>
<P>
Major factors for the strong economic growth include the
significant rise of oil price and introduction and acceleration of
economic reforms in the region. Average oil price registered a
20.3 percent increase in 1996, reaching 20.29 dollars per barrel
and the highest since 1990.
</P>
<P>
But, the unstable political situation caused by the stalling of
the Middle East peace process and economic sanctions on Iraq
hindered the region's growth rate to a certain degree.
</P>
<P>
Exports in the region increased by 15 percent and its imports
recorded a 9 percent growth in 1996. Exports of the Gulf
Cooperation Council (GCC) countries, namely Bharain, Kuwait, Oman,
Qatar, Saudi Arabia and the United Arab Emirates, came to 117.4
billion dollars, accounting for 89 percent of the region's total
and recording a 16 percent growth over the previous year. Exports
from other countries in the region registered a 5.6 percent growth
in 1996.
</P>
<P>
The region's balance of trade recorded a surplus of 30.5
billion dollars in 1996, much higher than the 21.7 billion dollars
the year before.
</P>
<P>
However, high unemployments remain a major problem in the
region, despite the significant growth rate. The highest
unemployment rate in the region was reported in the West Bank and
the Gaza Strip, affecting 28 percent of the labor force there;
second came Yemen with an estimated unemployment rate of 25
percent. Egypt and Jordan had a relatively high unemployment rate,
estimated at 13 percent. Even some GCC countries suffer from
unemployment among their indigenous populations because of
unrealistic expectations of the nationals and mismatch between job
seekers' qualifications and job opportunities. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970516.0048 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-16 </DATE_TIME>
