<HEADLINE> German Parliament Gives Green Light to Punish Marital Rape </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, May 15 (Xinhua) -- After over 25 years of legal
hagglings, the lower house of the German parliament today finally
passed a bill to make rape within a marriage a punishable crime:
offenders will face at least one year in jail.
</P>
<P>
The bill was approved today in the parliament's lower house,
known as the Bundestag, by an overwhelming majority of 471 to 138
with 35 abstentions.
</P>
<P>
Horst Eylmann, who chairs the Bundestag's Legal Committee,
commented that with the repeal of unequal legal treatment between
marital and extra-marital rapes, which could date back to last
century, "a legal fossil was buried."
</P>
<P>
According to Ulla Schmidt, a parliament member of the main
opposition in Bonn -- the Social Democratic Party, one seventh of
German women are raped once during their lifetime, and in most of
the cases, the offenders are their husbands. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
