<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Coffee Futures Top 20-Year Highs in New York </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, May 15 (Xinhua) -- Coffee futures prices soared to
20-year highs today in New York after Colombian exporters said the
country's crop will be much lower than official estimates, raising
the probability of world shortages by fall.
</P>
<P>
Coffee futures jumped an average 6 percent, closing in on 3
U.S. dollars a pound, after Gabriel Rosas, president of Colombia's
National Association of Coffee Exporters, predicted the world's
second-largest producer behind Brazil will harvest "a little bit
under 10 million bags" of arabica coffee for 1997-98.
</P>
<P>
It would be the second year of meager Colombian production,
making it likely that roasters and consumers will see much higher
prices in coming months.
</P>
<P>
It has been reported that Colombia's total crop production,
because of heavy rains, will fall to just 9.5 million bags,
compared with normal production of slightly more than 13 million
bags. Each bag weighs 132 pounds.
</P>
<P>
Many coffee-producing countries have curtailed production in
recent years amid sharply lower prices and were caught unawares by
the shortage.
</P>
<P>
The Brazilian Association of Coffee Exporters said Wednesday
the 1997-98 harvest will yield 24 million bags, up from 23.2
million estimated earlier. The estimate for arabica beans was
revised to 19.5 million bags from 18.7 million bags. But the
increase was below the average 27 million bags and was so slight
it will not make a difference.
</P>
<P>
Green, arabica coffee for May delivery on New York's Coffee,
Sugar &AMP; Cocoa Exchange rose 15.55 cents to settle at 2.771 U.S.
dollars a pound, the highest since mid-1977. The active July
contract jumped 14.6 cents to 2.55 U.S. dollars a pound. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
