<HEADLINE> 767 observers to Monitor Legislative Elections in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YAOUNDE, May 15 (Xinhua) -- Some 767 national and
international observers are in the country to monitor the may 17
legislative elections, Camerounian Vice-Premier Gilbert Andze
Tsoungui said today.
</P>
<P>
The Vice-Premier in charge of territorial administration made
the statements this evening when he was briefing with journalists
of the national and international press.
</P>
<P>
According to Tsoungui, among 767 observers, 78 are
international observers, 689 are national observers. They came
from the Commonwealth, the French Agency for Cultural and
Technical Cooperation, the BBC, the Frontation France Afrique,
the Italian, American and Britain embassies in Cameroun, the
National Human Rights Commission among other international and
non-governmental organizations.
</P>
<P>
Tsoungui said that that although the printing of candidate
lists is still going on, all will be ready before the voting
begins on saturday morning. The printing of all materials would
have been rounded up today, he added.
</P>
<P>
On the measures taken to avoid people from voting more than
once, Tsoungui said before voting day, all the national borders
will be closed.
</P>
<P>
To justify why the government rejected the idea of the
creation of an independent electoral commission, the vice-premier
said that such an organ is unconstitutional. Even if in advanced
democratic countries, such bodies did not exist, he added.
</P>
