<HEADLINE> UK PM Ready to Ease Ban on Contact with Sinn Fein </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, May 16 (Xinhua) -- Britain's new Prime Minister Tony
Blair said today he was ready to ease a ban on official contacts
with Sinn Fein, the political wing of the IRA, if it renounced
violence in its campaign to end British rule in Northern Ireland.
</P>
<P>
He said he would allow his government officials to meet Sinn
Fein if the Irish Republican Army did not carry out further acts
of violence.
</P>
<P>
The previous Conservative government banned official contacts
with Sinn Fein after the IRA ended a 17-month ceasefire in
February 1996 and started bomb attacks again to try to win an
unconditional place at the Northern Ireland peace talks.
</P>
<P>
"I am prepared to allow officials to meet Sinn Fein provided
events on the ground, here and elsewhere, do not make that
impossible," he said in a speech at a Belfast farming fair.
</P>
<P>
Blair arrived in Belfast earlier today for his first tour
outside London since he became prime minister two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
But he said only an unequivocal IRA ceasefire would allow Sinn
Fein to take part in Northern Ireland peace talks which will
resume on June 3.
</P>
<P>
"Violence has no place in a democratic society, whatever the
motivation of those practicing it," the prime minister said. IRA
has been striving for an end to British rule in Northern Ireland
through armed struggle for the past 28 years.
</P>
<P>
Sinn Fein leader Gerry Adams and its political negotiator
Martin McGuinness have called on the new Labor government to
reopen contact with the party since it won seats in the British
parliament in the May 1 general election.
</P>
<P>
Blair said he would not make concessions to Northern Ireland's
Catholic Irish nationalists who want to unite Northern Ireland
with its southern neighbor, the Republic of Ireland.
</P>
<P>
"My agenda is not a united Ireland, and I wonder just how many
see it as a realistic possibility in the foreseeable
future. Northern Ireland will remain part of the United Kingdom as
long as the majority here wish," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
