<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Railways Operating Well After Speed Lift </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 16 (Xinhua) -- China's railways, which handle 50
percent of the country's passengers and 70 percent of its freight,
are gradually adapting to the new operational scheme that was
launched April 1 to raise the speed of major passenger express
trains.
</P>
<P>
This was learned from the Ministry of Railways, which has been
making efforts to enhance the viability of the country's railways
amid the increasingly fierce transport market in which it is
challenged by highway carriers and airliners.
</P>
<P>
Raising the speed of the trains while upgrading the existing
lines is seen as a quick and economical method as well as a new
battle to win back the traditional share of the transport market
which had long been dominated by the railways, some local experts
say.
</P>
<P>
Since April 1 a new timetable has been in operation, and eight
pairs of passenger expresses shuttling between Beijing and major
Chinese cities are now running at 140 kph, while all other
passenger expresses running on the country's four railway trunk
lines have had their speeds boosted to 120 kph.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, 228 cargo-trains have become the country's first to
operate in accordance with a set timetable. In the past, nobody
knew what time their goods shipped by train would get to their
destinations, which often caused disputes among the railways and
their clients.
</P>
<P>
With the speedier expresses and freight trains, the ministry
wants to make the railways more attractive than their competitors,
in a bid to curb the steady and notable decline in passenger and
cargo-handling volumes in recent years.
</P>
<P>
According to the latest statistics from the ministry, in April
the railways carried 133.69 million tons of goods, 1.1 percent
less than in the same month of last year, while 307.43 million
passengers, 0.9 percent more, traveled by train. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970516.0059 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More Foreign Funds May Enter U.S. Telecommunications </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, May 16 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. Federal Communications
Commission is likely to soften its restriction on foreign
ownership in the country's telecommunications industry.
</P>
<P>
According to a report of the USA Today, The FCC will write a
new rule on the issue, which could start as early as May 22.
</P>
<P>
Foreign ownership of U.S. wireless carriers and international
long-distance carriers is currently limited to a 20 percent direct
investment and an additional indirect stake of 25 percent, the
paper said.
</P>
<P>
There are several forces spelling the end of those
restrictions, it said.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. is party to a World Trade Organization agreement
signed in February that opens telecommunications markets around
the world. The FCC's current restrictions conflict with that
agreement.
</P>
<P>
U.S. wireless carriers desperately need access to global
investors. Many small carriers are having trouble paying for
licenses they won in FCC auctions and need foreign capital.
</P>
<P>
This is also an opportunity for companies that had trouble
raising capital in the United States to find partners abroad,
according analysts.
</P>
<P>
New rules could also spark a wave of mergers and
acquisitions, the paper said. They would make it easier for
big foreign companies to buy smaller U.S. firms.
</P>
<P>
It could also be a good news for U.S. consumers who will
enjoy lower prices of international calls. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
