<HEADLINE> Chinese Premier Meets French President (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 16 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Premier Li Peng said here
today that state leaders of China and France have opened a new
chapter in Sino-French relations with their determination to
comprehensively deepen bilateral co-operation, proceeding from the
present new world situation.
</P>
<P>
This is of far-reaching significance for promoting the trend of
multi-polarization of the world and the formation of a new
international pattern, Li told visiting French President Jacques
Chirac during their meeting.
</P>
<P>
Extending a warm welcome to Chirac, Li said that the Chinese
government highly appreciates the French president's contribution
to the improvement of Sino-French cooperation and the overall
development of bilateral relations since he took office.
</P>
<P>
Li described Chirac's visit as an important event in the
history of Sino-French ties. He said that China and France have
signed a series of important agreements and several contracts or
letters of intent on economic and trade cooperation during the
president's current visit.
</P>
<P>
What is more important is that Chinese President Jiang Zemin
and President Chirac have reached common understanding on a series
of issues and signed the Sino-French Joint Declaration, which he
said has demonstrated to the world the two countries' willingness
and determination to set up a comprehensive partnership oriented
to the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
Chirac expressed his pleasure at visiting China as French
president. Over the past two years contacts and communications
between the two countries have witnessed considerable increase, he
noted, adding that he himself has defined the direction and
principles for the development of the overall mutually-beneficial
relations of cooperation.
</P>
<P>
The Sino-French Joint Declaration signed today is the most
important document in Sino-French relations signed since 1964, and
the two countries showed their resolve to keep close political
links and develop reciprocally beneficial economic and trade
co-operation, he said, expressing satisfaction over his current
China tour.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970516.0066 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Premier Meets French President (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
On bilateral economic and trade ties, Li said that both China
and France enjoy advantages in their economies, which are highly
complimentary and of great potential for cooperation.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese government attaches much importance to the
promotion of economic and trade relations between the two
countries, and considers it a major component of the comprehensive
partnership between the two countries, the premier said, adding
that economic and trade relations have witnessed rapid progress
since Chirac assumed office.
</P>
<P>
Through concerted efforts of both sides, China and France have
signed a framework agreement on China's purchase of 100-seater
aircraft and a contract and letter of intent to buy 30 Airbus
airplanes and ten ATR planes, respectively. They also declared the
opening of business of French insurance companies and banks in
China, Li said.
</P>
<P>
The Sino-French Joint Declaration has also set the direction
for the further development of bilateral economic and trade
cooperation, which shows that China and France have scored new and
substantial results in their co-operation, Li said.
</P>
<P>
With China's economic development there is great potential for
cooperation between the two countries so long as the two make
practical joint efforts, he noted.
</P>
<P>
Chirac agreed with Li. He pointed out that France is one of the
world's strongest economies, and China is witnessing rapid
economic progress and enjoys a big market, which means great
potential for the two countries' economic and trade
cooperation. France and China should try to reinforce and expand
such co-operation, he added.
</P>
<P>
Chirac said that France fully supports China's early entry into
the World Trade Organization (WTO), as the WTO cannot afford to
leave such an important country as China out.
</P>
<P>
Li briefed Chirac on his recent African tour and China's policy
toward the African countries.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that to develop Sino-African relations facing the
21st century is conducive to the promotion of world
multi-polarization, adding that future Sino-African economic and
trade relations will be based on the principles of equality and
mutual benefit.
</P>
<P>
Chirac noted that the pessimistic attitude held by some people
toward the future of Africa is incorrect, and it is wise of China
to work for the development of Sino-African ties. He also
described Li's African tour as positive and successful.
</P>
<P>
Wang Zhongyu, head of the Chinese Government Reception
Committee and minister in charge of the State Economic and Trade
Commission, Herve de Charette, French foreign minister, and other
senior Chinese and French officials attended the meeting. 
</P>
</TEXT>
