<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Bank to Give Manila Huge Loans </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, May 16 (Xinhua) -- The World Bank has agreed to provide
1.13 billion U.S. dollars in loans to the Philippines in the next
three years, the official Philippine News Agency reported today.
</P>
<P>
The agreement was reached during a recent week-long annual
meeting on the Country Portfolio Performance Review and
Programming Mission between the Philippine government and the
World Bank in Washington, the agency said.
</P>
<P>
The three-year lending program will address the government's
priority concerns which include human resource development,
poverty eradication, sustainable development and efficient public
sector management.
</P>
<P>
According to the reports, infrastructure and agriculture will
receive the bulk of the loans committed by the World Bank, the
country's second biggest multilateral donor after the Asian
Development Bank.
</P>
<P>
The world leading financial body will also extend technical
assistance in the form of economic and sector work, particularly
in the areas of economic management, rural development, health and
energy, the reports said.
</P>
<P>
To help develop Mindanao in the southern Philippines, the World
Bank has agreed to establish a 10-million-dollar fund to finance
small-scale projects for livelihood, infrastructure and basic
services requirements of communities in the region.  
</P>
</TEXT>
