<HEADLINE> Sidek to Miss Sudirman Cup and World Championships </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GLASGOW, May 16 (Xinhua) -- Rashid Sidek of Malaysia, who won
an Olympic badminton men's singles bronze in 1996, was not
selected for the national team for the Sudirman Cup world mixed
team championship and the world championships to start here on
Monday.
</P>
<P>
Sidek failed to report on time for the Malaysian national
team's training and "does not make himself available for the
Sudirman Cup", Malaysian head coach Morten Frost told Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
Sidek, now world number 11 and Malaysia's second best player
after sixth-ranked Ong Ewe Hock, did not appear for training by
the deadline three or four weeks ago, said the Danish-born Frost,
who took over the team only three months ago.
</P>
<P>
Four-time All-England champion Frost said Sidek could neither
compete at the world championships because "we come here as a team
(for both events) but Sidek doesn't make himself for the Sudirman
Cup".
</P>
<P>
Frost said he did not know whether Nusa Mahsuri, the
professional badminton club which Sidek plays for, was invovled in
Sidek's decision.
</P>
<P>
Chen Kang, a former Chinese international who is now the coach
for Malaysian doubles team, said Sidek's club is frequently at
odds with the Malaysian Badminton Association.
</P>
<P>
"Sidek's club is a professional badminton club but the
Malaysian Badminton Association is mainly amateur. So there are
frictions." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970516.0077 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan's Securities Reform Proposals Published </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, May 16 (Xinhua) -- The long awaited shake up of the
Japanese securities market came a step closer today after a
government advisory panel proposed a package of drastic measures
to deregulate securities trading.
</P>
<P>
The move is part of Prime Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto's promise
to effect a sweeping "Big Bang"-style financial reform by 2001, Kyodo
News reported.
</P>
<P>
An interim report drawn up by the Securities and Exchange
Council (SEC) put forward a wide range of measures to make the
Japanese market more competitive, ranging from lowering the
securities transaction tax, easing securities licensing
requirements and diversifing financial instruments, to
deregulating listed stock trading and forming a legal framework
for increasing electronic commerce.
</P>
<P>
The core of the package is a proposal for liberalizing
brokerage commission fees in stock trading ahead of 2001, the
government's target date for completing financial reform.
</P>
<P>
The proposal calls for lowering the minimum trading value
subject to free rate-setting by brokerages to 100 million yen(0.9
million dollars) from 1 billion yen (900 million dollars) in April
1998.
</P>
<P>
It also recommends brokerages be free to set their own stock
trading commission rates by 2001.
</P>
<P>
Other business sectors are to be encouraged to enter the
securities business by requiring them to merely report their
intention to the Finance Ministry.
</P>
<P>
Tax on securities transactions are to be lowered to make it
easier for individual investors to take part in securities
trading.
</P>
<P>
The interim report, prepared by three teams of experts under
the SEC, will be finalized by mid-June. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
