<DOCNO> XIE19970516.0082 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkish Fighters Airraid PKK Camps </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, May 16 (Xinhua) -- Turkish F-4 fighters and Cobra
helicopter gunships today again bombarded the camps of the
outlawed Kurdish Workers' Party (PKK) in northern Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The jet fighters took off from the air bases in Diyarbakir
and Erhac, southeastern Malatya province, early this morning and
made 30 sorties to airraid the northern Iraqi regions of Sinat,
Haftanin, Hakurk, Kesan and Sarisavaklar, where the PKK rebels
are based, according to the semi-official Anatolia News Agency.
</P>
<P>
Following the bombardment of the Turkish fighter planes, the
Cobra helicopter gunships strongly attacked the PKK-based five
areas in northern Iraq, said the agency.
</P>
<P>
With the support of artillery fire, the Turkish security
forces and some 150 village guards battled the PKK militants in
the Sarisavaklar region.
</P>
<P>
About 50,000-strong Turkish government troops crossed into
northern Iraq Wednesday, and fighting is continuing in the places
of Sinat, Sivi, Begova, Kanimazi, Batufa and Hakurk in the region.
</P>
<P>
Most of the PKK rebels are fleeing toward the Iranian border
and a small group toward the Turkish-Iraqi border, the agency said.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish military operation, the largest in scale over the
past few years, followed a call for aid by Iraq's Kurdistan
Democratic Party (KDP) Chairman Mesud Barzani.
</P>
<P>
Iraq has strongly protested the Turkish military campaign
against the PKK.
</P>
<P>
The PKK has been fighting a separatist war for autonomy in
southeastern Turkey since August 1984. Its armed wing, based in
northern Iraq, has been waging hit-and-run battles against the
government forces. 
</P>
</TEXT>
