<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Step up Reform of State-Owned Enterprises </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 16 (Xinhua) -- The State Council, China's highest
administrative body, has decided to establish more pilot
enterprise groups to step up the reform of state-owned enterprises.
</P>
<P>
According to a circular just issued by the State Planning
Commission and two other central departments, the number of pilot
enterprise groups will be increased from 57 to 120, and these big
firms will play the leading role in some key industries of the
national economy.
</P>
<P>
A modern industrial mechanism will be introduced into these
enterprises, which are expected to operate with a rational
economic structure and strong competitiveness.
</P>
<P>
They will operate on their own, and assume sole responsibility
for their profits or losses, according to the circular.
</P>
<P>
The move is expected to allocate and distribute industrial
materials and resources in a more rational manner, and these
enterprises will serve as engines for reforming more state firms.
</P>
<P>
The functions of the government and the enterprises should be
separated, and inter-regional or trans-industrial cooperation
should be encouraged, so as to enable the government to exercise
better macro control.
</P>
<P>
In these enterprises there should be a clear relationship
between the parent companies and the subsidiary companies, the
circular stipulated.
</P>
<P>
The parent companies should have the authority to decide on the
introduction of foreign-financed projects worth up to 30 million
US dollars. In addition, some of the enterprises will have the
authority to handle foreign trade, the circular said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
