<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Raising Funds for South China Nuclear Power Station </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENZHEN, May 15 (Xinhua) -- China's State Development Bank
(SDB) had extended 100 million U.S. dollars worth of credit to the
Ling'ao Nuclear Power Station (LNPS) in south China's Guangdong
Province and raised 400 million U.S. dollars in international
commercial loans for the project by the end of April, Yao Zhenyan,
the bank's president said.
</P>
<P>
Yao was here for a ceremony marking the official start of
construction of LNPS yesterday and told reporters that his bank
had signed 2.3 billion U.S. dollars worth of export credit and
loans agreements for the project and will be responsible for
raising 1.8 billion U.S. dollars in international commercial loans
for construction work.
</P>
<P>
Other participants in the fund-raising are France's Banque
Nationale de Paris and Britain's West Merchant Bank.
</P>
<P>
The Shenzhen Branch of the China Industrial and Commercial Bank
will be SDB's agent, provide more efficient banking services for
the project.
</P>
<P>
LNPS is located in Shenzhen City, 1.2 km from the Daya Bay
Nuclear Power Station, and is being built at an estimated cost of
four billion U.S. dollars. It is one of the biggest projects of
the Ninth Five-Year Plan (1996-2000) in scale and overseas
investment.
</P>
<P>
Four one-million-kw nuclear power generating units are planned
for the station, with two to be set up in the first phase of
construction, and which will begin commercial operation in July of
2002 and March of 2003. 
</P>
</TEXT>
