<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> BIS Official Lauds China's Financial Reforms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 16 (Xinhua) -- China has achieved remarkable
results in economic development and financial reforms, though it
still has some issues to address, a senior official of the Bank
for International Settlements (BIS) said here today.
</P>
<P>
"China has performed remarkably well in recent years," BIS
General Manager Andrew Crockett said in an interview with Chinese
reporters.
</P>
<P>
He lauded China's success last year in maintaining a high
economic growth rate while cutting inflation significantly.
</P>
<P>
China's gross domestic product, which had been growing nearly
ten percent annually for several years, rose 9.7 percent last
year, whereas its inflation rate measured by the retail price
index went down to 6.1 percent, as against 14.8 percent in 1995
and 21.7 percent in 1994.
</P>
<P>
"As a visitor, one is impressed by the manner in which the
continuation of healthy growth has been combined with a reduction
in the rate of inflation," Crockett said. "That is a very
difficult combination to achieve for a soft landing."
</P>
<P>
China has done as well as any other country in achieving an
economic soft landing, which he said refers to sustaining a high
rate of development and investment while preserving a strong
currency and reducing inflation to a very low level.
</P>
<P>
Crockett said that China's banking reforms have achieved
significant progress, and the People's Bank of China, the central
bank, has played a major part in the realization of the present
good economic situation.
</P>
<P>
China is moving in the direction of applying market-oriented
measures for sustainable growth, he said, adding that the good
economic indicators reflect very much the activities of the
central bank and the instruments it has used.
</P>
<P>
In spite of the progress already made, China has yet to address
a number of issues in the financial sector, the manager pointed
out.
</P>
<P>
He pledged that the BIS, which sets standards for international
banking practices, will support China's effort to further its
financial reforms by providing technical assistance in payment and
settlement services.
</P>
<P>
Often referred to as a club of central banks, the BIS currently
has 41 member banks. China joined the international financial body
last November. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
