<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Retains Top Berth in East Asian Games </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PUSAN, May 16 (Xinhua) -- China had an influx of nine gold medals
on Friday to retain its top berth at the second East Asian Games as a
total of 124 gold medals were pocketed by the athletes from nine
countries and regions.
</P>
<P>
From the 11 track and field finals, the trio of China, Japan and
Kazakhstan won three gold apiece with South Korea taking the remaining
two.
</P>
<P>
China stood atop with 44 golds, beating Japan to second on 34 and
South Korea third on 23, while Mongolia opened its gold account with
three from the freestyle wrestling competitions.
</P>
<P>
"We were making our steady steps in the games as our athletes
retained their top forms, and we hope more gold medals from the track
and field events in the coming days," said Wu Shaozhang, Chef de
Mission of the Chinese delegation.
</P>
<P>
On Friday, Kudok Stadium ushered in three Chinese veteran champions
in athletics, including the eldest 30-year-old Li Tong in the Chinese
squad. Three Chinese lifters outpaced their rivals as Xiong Guoming
notched up his first gold as the swimming competition concluded.
</P>
<P>
Song Zhaomei set a new world record by jerking 135.5 kgs en route
to winning the women's 83-kg weightlifting title as Shan Yulong took
the women's over 83kg category and Cui Wenhua won the men's 108kg
title.
</P>
<P>
Li Tong and Chen Yanhao finished one-two for China in the men's 110
meter hurdles by clocking in 13.67 and 13.70 seconds respectively.
</P>
<P>
Li Tong, current Asian record holder who broke the marks 18 times,
said "we are strong in the discipline, and I alway win over teammate
Chen in international meets while he kept his clean slate against me
at home."
</P>
<P>
Zhang Lianbiao, 28, who ranked 11th in Atlanta Olympics, took the
javelin title with his second attempt of 77.80 meters, surpassing his
own games record of 77.56 set in Shanghai in 1993.
</P>
<P>
Jin Ling, Asian record holder of 1.97 meters set in 1989 Japan,
cleared 1.91 meters to take the women's high jump title, beating
Svetlana Zalevskaia of Kazakhstan to second in 1.88 meters who had her
personal best of 1.98 meters set in Pierae Benite, Russia in 1996.
</P>
<P>
"I was not sure to win the gold medal, but I was also not to
surrender nothing without exerting my every efforts," said the
1.83-meter slender mother athlete of a two-year-old girl baby.
</P>
<P>
Japan won three gold medals through Yuka Mitsumori in the women's
10,000-meter walk, Yvonne Kanazawa in the women's 100-meter hurdles
and Yasunori Uchitomi in the men's 3,000-meter steeplechase.
</P>
<P>
South Korean Son Ju-il sprinted ahead to take the men's 400 meters
title in 45.84 and compatriot Kim Tae-keun outscored a field of four
rivals to win the decathlon event with a total point of 7,372.
</P>
<P>
In the last-day swimming competitions, China stopped Japan from
making another clean sweep by taking two out of the last six gold
medals at stake through Zhu Yingwen in the women's 50m freestyle and
Xiong Guoming in the men's 200m individual medley.
</P>
<P>
However, the Japanese swimmers still boasted of a lion's share of
21 out of 31 gold medals, beating China to second with seven, South
Korea with two and Kazakhstan with one.
</P>
<P>
"The games opens a new epoch for a tough Sino-Japanese contest, the
Chinese swimmers have to double their efforts in order to retain their
top spot in Asia, otherwise, their peers from Japan will become the
dominating forces in the pool," said Chen Yunpeng, former head coach
of the Chinese swimming squad.
</P>
<P>
However, Japanese head coach Ueno Koji said "China would garner
most gold medals at the games should it send in its best swimmers
here."
</P>
<P>
Takashi Yamamoto became the sole four-time champions and the sole
swimmer to break the Asian record in the swimming competitions.
</P>
<P>
He clocked in the new record of 1:58.01 to take the men's 200m
butterfly on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Mongolia opened its gold account on Friday with all three from the
freestyle wrestling competitions through Oyunbileg Durevbaatar,
Bayanmunkh Gantogtokh and Dolgorsuren Sumiyabazar.
</P>
<P>
South Korea reapt 10 gold medals with three from judo, one from
weightlifting and two apiece from soft tennis, wrestling and the track
and field competitions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
