<DOCNO> XIE19970516.0104 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine Trade Deficit Increases Slightly </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, May 16 (Xinhua) -- The Philippines posted a trade
deficit of nearly 3 billion U.S. dollars in the first quarter this
year, an 8.4-percent increase over a year ago, the National
Statistics Office said today.
</P>
<P>
Compared to last year, cost of the Philippines' imported
merchandise rose by 14.2 percent to 8.4 billion dollars while
export receipts went up by 17.5 percent to 5.5 billion dollars,
according to figures released by the office.
</P>
<P>
But for March alone, the country's trade deficit was 934
million dollars, a 14.2-percent drop from about 1.1 billion
dollars a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
Accounting for 15.2 percent of the aggregate import bill for
March, electronics and components remained the top import
commodities, with payments for them amounting to 447 million
dollars.
</P>
<P>
Payments for raw materials and intermediate goods, mainly
semi-processed raw materials, which took up 45.3 percent of the
total cost of merchandise imports for March, increased by 0.9
percent to 1.3 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
With a 20.7-percent share, Japan remained the main source of
imported merchandise for the Philippines, which bought 607 million
dollars' worth of Japanese goods in the month.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
