<HEADLINE> KNU Leader's Assistant Surrenders in Myanmar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, May 16 (Xinhua) -- A personal assistant of the leader
of the Kayin National Union (KNU), the last largest remaining
anti-government ethnic armed group in Myanmar, has surrendered to
the government recently, official sources confirmed today.
</P>
<P>
Saw Di Moe, who is also an adviser to KNU leader Bo Mya on
trading matters, approached Myanmar authorities concerned to
"trade arms for peace" on May 4 at the Dah-Kwin camp, 250
kilometers northeast of Yangon near the Myanmar-Thai border, the
sources said.
</P>
<P>
The KNU, one of the 16 ethnic armed groups in Myanmar, has been
operating on the Myanmar-Thai border in armed opposition to the
government. It is also the last group which has not yet made peace
with the government although four rounds of peace talks have been
held.  
</P>
</TEXT>
