<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese, French Foreign Ministers Hold Lunch Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 16 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Vice-Premier and Foreign
Minister Qian Qichen and French Foreign Minister Herve De Charette
had a working luncheon here today, speaking highly of Sino-French
relations and French President Jacques Chirac's current visit to
China.
</P>
<P>
Qian said that in the past few years Sino-French friendly
cooperation in various fields has seen a substantial development,
and Chirac's present visit has promoted the the extensive and
in-depth development of bilateral cooperative relations.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the joint declaration signed here today by the
Chinese and French presidents shows the determination and
aspiration of both sides to further their ties and has laid a
foundation for bilateral cooperation in the future.
</P>
<P>
This is not only in the interests of the two countries, but also
conducive to world peace, stability and development, added Qian.
</P>
<P>
De Charette said that France-China relations have experienced
ups and downs since the two countries forged diplomatic ties,
while bilateral relations now have entered a period of long-term
and sound development.
</P>
<P>
Noting that Chirac's visit is a very important one, De
Charette said that the joint declaration signed here today is a
very important document concerning major issues in today's world,
and it shows that the two countries enjoy extensive consensus.
</P>
<P>
He expressed his conviction that bilateral cooperation in
various fields will continue to see sound development, and
that he hoped that the two foreign ministries would further make
positive efforts to this end.
</P>
<P>
Expressing their satisfaction with the exchanges and
consultations between the two foreign ministries, the foreign
ministers agreed to hold such consultations into a mechanism, so
as to continue the good momentum for two-way consultations at
various levels.
</P>
<P>
Qian asked De Charette to visit China again at the beginning of
next year at a time convenient to him, which was accepted with
pleasure by De Charette.
</P>
<P>
The two foreign ministers also exchanged views on bilateral
relations and international issues of common concern. 
</P>
</TEXT>
