<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Stops Japan from Sweeping Swimming Golds at E. Asian Games </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PUSAN, May 16 (Xinhua) -- China stopped Japan from making another
clean sweep by taking two out of the last six gold medals at stake on
the last-day swimming competitions at the second East Asian Games here
on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Zhu Yingwen of China clocked 26.14 seconds to take the women's
50-meter freestyle, beating Evguenia Ermakova of Kazakhstan to second
in 26.18 while her teammate Lu Bin returned home with a bronze medal
in 26.73.
</P>
<P>
Xiong Guoming of China notched up his first gold medal after six
day competitions by winning the men's 200-meter individual medley in
2:05.50. Koichi Masuta of Japan finished second in 2:06.09 and Wang
Haizhou awarded China another bronze in 2:06.75.
</P>
<P>
The day's other four gold medals were all taken by the Japanese
swimmers who stood atop with 21 out of 31 gold medals from the pool
where China bagged home seven, South Korea took two and Kazakhstan
with one.
</P>
<P>
"The games opens a new epoch for a tough Sino-Japanese contest, the
Chinese swimmers have to double their efforts in order to retain their
top spot in Asia, otherwise, their peers from Japan will become the
dominating forces in the pool," said Chen Yunpeng, former head coach
of the Chinese swimming squad.
</P>
<P>
Ueno Koji, head coach of the Japanese team, felt satisfied with the
feats achieved by his disciples at the East Asian Games, but remained
reluctant to forecast any possibility of overtaking China's top spot
in Asia, saying "China would garner most gold medals at the games
should it send in its best swimmers here."
</P>
<P>
On Thursday, Japan collected all six gold medals of the day,
leaving only three silvers for China and Kazakhstan and four bronzes
for both the host South Korea and Chinese Taipei.
</P>
<P>
Takashi Yamamoto became the sole four-time champions at the Games
as he paced a Japanese quartet to win the men's 4x100m medley relay in
a new games record of 3:44.15 on Friday. Masami Tanaka of Japan was
the only women triple gold medalists from the pool at the East Asian
Games.
</P>
<P>
And a new Asian record, the only one in the swimming pool, was set
by Takashi in Thursday's 200m butterfly final where he won in 1:58.01.
</P>
<P>
In the last-day competitions, Yuko Nakanishi touched home first in
the women's 200m butterfly in 2:12.98, beating Li Na of China to
second in 2:14.06 and Ayayi Aoyama of Japan to third in 2:15.21.
</P>
<P>
Miki Nakao led for a 1-2 finish for Japan in the women's 200-meter
backstroke final by touching home in 2:12, with Mai Nakamura taking
the silver medal in 2:12.76. Chinese Tao Xuan ranked third in 2:15.95.
</P>
<P>
The other gold went to Hisato Yasui in the men's 1,500m freestyle
who clocked in a winning time of 15:37.92, beating South Korean Lee
Kyu-chang and Chinese Jin Hao to second and third respectively.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
