<DOCNO> XIE19970516.0113 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 3 Israeli Soldiers Killed in S. Lebanon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, May 16 (Xinhua) -- Three Israeli soldiers and two
Hezbollah gunmen were killed Thursday night during fierce
clashes in South Lebanon, Israel Radio reported today.
</P>
<P>
About seven other Israeli soldiers were also wounded in the
fighting, which occurred two kilometers beyond the boundary of
the eastern sector of the Israeli-proclaimed south Lebanon
security zone. The clashes erupted when an Israeli paratroop unit
was ambushed by Hezbollah gunmen.
</P>
<P>
The fighting erupted around 9 p.m. Thursday night and
continued after midnight. Israel retaliated with heavy air and
artillery bombardments of the area, with over 350 shells being
fired within two hours, Israel Radio and televisions reported.
</P>
<P>
Thursday's fighting signaled the escalation of clashes
between the two sides. It was apparently an act of retaliation
launched by Hezbollah which lost four fighters on Monday in a
failed attempt to capture a position held by the pro-Israeli
South Lebanese Army in the eastern sector of the zone.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Israel Army has instructed troops in South Lebanon
to take precautions against possible kidnaping plot by the
Popular Front for the Liberation of Palestine, a Syria-based
anti-Israeli Palestinian group.
</P>
<P>
Israeli military officials have charged Iran for having
shipped large quantities of weapons to Hezbollah via Syria in the
past four months. He said the shipments may include some more
advanced weapons, such as long-range Katyusha rockets capable of
reaching Israel's Haifa port in the north.
</P>
<P>
A military officer from the northern command was quoted as
saying that the new weapons acquired by Hezbollah are affecting
the operation of Israeli military helicopters by preventing them
from penetrating further north. But he added that Israel could
find ways to cope with the problem. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
