<HEADLINE> HK Supreme Court Adopts Chinese Language in Civil Proceedings </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, May 16 (Xinhua) -- Either Chinese or English can be
used in Hong Kong's Supreme Court civil proceedings, it was
announced here today.
</P>
<P>
A judiciary spokesman said that the publication of the new
Rules is an important step towards bilingualism in court. It
allows civil proceedings in the Supreme Court to be conducted in
either or both of the official languages.
</P>
<P>
At present, English has been the only official language in the
High Court, except appeals from the Magistracies, Small Claims
Tribunal and Labor Tribunal. While under the Rule, litigants may
file their documents in court in either Chinese or English.
</P>
<P>
"A judge may choose either of the official languages in the
whole or any part of the proceedings for the just and expeditious
disposal of cases," the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
Another step towards bilingualism in court would be made on
June 2 when appeals from the Minor Employment Claims Adjudication
Board could also be heard in either or both of the official
languages, he said.
</P>
<P>
Since 1974, either English or Chinese can be used in the
Magistracies. Restriction on the use of the Chinese language in
the District Court and the Lands Tribunal was lifted in February
1996. Some other similar restrictions were lifted in December
1996, according to the announcement. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
