<HEADLINE> World Tourism Body Predicts Growth in Macao Tourism </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MACAO, May 16 (Xinhua) -- A leading official of the World
Tourism Organization (WTO) predicts that Macao's tourism sector
will see "ideal growth" well until 2010.
</P>
<P>
Francesco Frangialli, secretary-general of the Madrid-based
WTO, said at a two-day meeting of the WTO's Commission for East
Asia and the Pacific, which concluded here today, that Macao's
tourism will achieve continuous growth in the coming years.
</P>
<P>
"Following the opening of the Macao International Airport and
the vigorous efforts to cultivate long-distance market, Macao's
tourism will see an ideal growth within this century and well
beyond the first decade in the 21st century," he said.
</P>
<P>
Tourism remains a dominant source of revenue in the tiny
territory with 410,000 residents. More than 8.15 million visitors
toured Macao last year, up 5.14 percent from 1995.
</P>
<P>
Macao's casinos, annual grand prix, art festival, music
festival, luxury hotels and services plus buildings of both
Chinese and Western styles make it an attractive destination for
holiday-makers, observers said.
</P>
<P>
Frangialli pledged that the WTO will continue to support Macao
in its tourism expansion and in the promotion of its tourism
market.
</P>
<P>
About 150 delegates from 22 countries and regions and 12 local
and international tourism and aviation entities attended the
meeting.  
</P>
</TEXT>
