<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Regions Summit Debates on European Integration </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMSTERDAM, May 16 (Xinhua) -- Local and regional leaders and
representatives in the European Union (EU) today started
discussions on how the regions and cities could better contribute
to the European integration.
</P>
<P>
The Summit of the Regions and Cities, opening here on Thursday
with about 300 participants, was focused on issues of employment,
enlargement and the EU's institutional reform.
</P>
<P>
The meeting was held before leaders of the 15 EU member states
meet here in July to conclude the Intergovernmental Conference
(IGC) launched in March last year so as to revise the Maastricht
Treaty.
</P>
<P>
Germany's Baravian Prime Minister Edmund Stoiber and Mayor of
the Portuguese city of Oporto Fernando Gomes will draft a report
on the meeting and submit it to the July summit.
</P>
<P>
At the meeting which is important for the Committee of Regions
(CoR), EU's consultative assembly on regional affairs, Stoiber
called for closer ties between the EU and its regions as well as
more involvement of the regional authorities in the process and
implementation of EU's policy making.
</P>
<P>
"Europe must no longer be allowed to restrict the scope of
action of the regions and cities," he said, adding that "instead
it must promote direct responsibility and dynamism on the part of
the regions and cities, for instance in structural policy,
agricultural policy and community aid."
</P>
<P>
Stoiber also urged greater contribution of the regions and
local authorities to reduce the distance between the EU and its
citizens so as to make the European integration more transparent.
</P>
<P>
Reports said the CoR has called for the IGC to rewrite the
Article 3 in the Maastricht Treaty, which sets a division of
responsibility between EU and its member states.
</P>
<P>
The CoR wants to ensure that the new treaty contains a specific
reference to the role of the regions and local authorities in
implementation of "subsidiariness", a concept which means all
action in the public domain must be entrusted to the lowest
institutional level of government.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970516.0127 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-16 10:48 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iranian President Warns Against Election Frauds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, May 16 (Xinhua) -- Iranian President Akbar Hashemi
Rafsanjani today warned Interior Ministry officials against any
play around ballot boxes as the countdown starts on the
presidential election scheduled on May 23.
</P>
<P>
Addressing thousands of audience at the Friday prayer on the
campus of the Tehran University, Rafsanjani noted it would be
"treason, sin and theft" if the public votes are played around by
officials in charge of the elections.
</P>
<P>
"The change of public votes would have very negative impact
on the society. The people will lose their trust in the
system. This treason will be unforgivable," warned the
64-year-old president.
</P>
<P>
Observers here noted that Rafsanjani's statement reflected a
major concern of the public who feel that officials from the
Interior Ministry in charge of ballot boxes would play around the
votes in favor of their favored presidential candidates.
</P>
<P>
Hardliner Parliament Speaker Ali Akbar Nateq-Nouri is the
front-runner among the four contenders. But local observers say
that Nateq-Nouri is facing powerful challenge by his main rival
Seyed Mohammad Khatami, former minister of culture and Islamic
guidance, who is gaining more and more support from the
intellectual circles and citizens in big cities.
</P>
<P>
A specialist analyzed that Nateq-Nouri would win 60 percent
of votes in rural areas and small cities while Khatami would win
60 percent votes in big cities.
</P>
<P>
The statement by the moderate president on the eve of the
presidential elections also showed that the power struggle in
the Islamic regime is intensifying day by day.
</P>
<P>
However, Rafsanjani still called on the public to actively
turn out at the elections, saying "it is the national and
Islamic duty for everyone to cast its vote in the elections. No
one should have any excuse not to vote."
</P>
<P>
He also advised the contenders not to accuse each other or
defame other candidates during the elections.
</P>
<P>
On May 10, Iran launched a nationwide presidential campaign
with main streets inundated with colorful banners, flags and
pictures of presidential candidates.
</P>
<P>
Leaflets of candidates have been distributed door to door
among millions of Iranian households in early morning or in the
evening.
</P>
<P>
This is the 7th presidential elections since the Islamic
revolution led by late Ayatollah Khomeini toppled the Pahlavi
Dynasty and declared the founding of the Islamic Republic of Iran
in on April, 1979. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
