<HEADLINE> Nigeria, Togo Call for Ceasefire in Zaire </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, May 16 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria's head of state General Sani
Abacha and Togolese President Gnassingbe Eyadema have called for
an early ceasefire and cessation of hostilities in Zaire.
</P>
<P>
They noted that although the recent talks between the
embattled President Mobuto Sese Seko and Laurent Kabila of the
Democratic Alliance for the Liberation of Congo-Zaire were
welcome, an immediate end to all hostilities had become
imperative to avert bloodshed.
</P>
<P>
In a communique released on Thursday after a one-day official
visit by the Togolese president, both leaders re-affirmed
necessity of orderly ascension to power through a democratic and
peaceful process in Zaire.
</P>
<P>
On recent develoments in other parts of the continent,
especially the Great Lakes region and the Horn of Africa, the two
leaders re-affirmed the need for a concerted action by African
governments to tackle the menace of conflicts on the continent.
</P>
<P>
They welcomed the outcome of the recent extraordinary summit
of the Organization of African Unity Central Organ Mechanism for
Conflict Prevention, Management and Resolution, held in Lome,
Togo on the situation of Zaire.
</P>
<P>
As leaders of the west African sub-region and members of the
Economic Community of West African States (ECOWAS), they reviewed
the Liberian situation and acknowledged the important role played
by countries in the region in the search for peace, particularly
the sacrifice being made by the ECOWAS peacekeeping force known
as ECOMOG.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the success in the disarmament and
demobilization exercise gained in accordance with the Abuja peace
accord, they called on all interested parties in the conflict to
pool resources to ensure free and fair elections in Liberia.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
