<BODY>
<HEADLINE> British Companies in HK Optimistic About Future </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, May 16 (Xinhua) -- British businesses in Hong Kong
are generally confident in their future development, according to
the result of a recent survey.
</P>
<P>
The survey, conducted by the British Chamber of Commerce, found
that 93 percent of companies replying to the questionnaire
confirmed they hoped still to be operating in Hong Kong in 2000.
</P>
<P>
Chairman of the chamber Patrick Paul said: "The overwhelming
message is of confidence and commitment to Hog Kong. Perceptions
abroad that Hong Kong is in some sort of crisis are totally
unfounded."
</P>
<P>
Access to China came out as the area which the chamber's
members were most optimistic about, and over 80 percent of them
saw the access improving.
</P>
<P>
Sino-British trade relations are another area of optimism, with
more than half the respondents expecting they would improve.
</P>
<P>
When asked if British firms might face discrimination because
of their colonial past, executive director of the chamber
Christopher Hammerbeck said he expected a level playing field to
be maintained in terms of awarding contracts.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970516.0138 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenyan Coffee Prices Continue to Rise </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, May 16 (Xinhua) -- Kenyan coffee prices will continue
to rally in the near term after touching highest levels since
1994, thanks to the global shortage of mild Arabica coffees, the
Kenyan Times newspaper reported today.
</P>
<P>
If good weather prevails, there will be a harvest of
100,000-to-110,000 tons of coffee in 1997/98 in the eastern
African country, the report quoted local traders as saying.
</P>
<P>
At the weekly export auction on Tuesday, quality coffees
gained up to 30 Dollars per 50 kilograms on speculative buying.
</P>
<P>
The traders say prices are a major incentive for farmers to
improve coffee production, threatened in the 1996/97 fiscal year
to end in September by coffee berry diseases from June to July
last year and drought between December and March this year.
</P>
<P>
It was estimated that the 1996/97 coffee production in Kenya
will at most reach 80,000 tons compared with 97,575 tons in
1995/96 and 95,806 tons in 1994/95, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
Premium grade ABs averaged 439 Dollars per 50 kilograms
compared to 403 Dollars last week while grade AAs sold at 451
Dollars from 417 Dollars, according to data from Kenyan Coffee
Auctions Ltd.
</P>
<P>
Traders here put sale prices even higher, at between 472
Dollars and 540 Dollars FAQ (Fair Average Quality) for AAs and
between 462 Dollars and 520 Dollars for ABs.
</P>
<P>
Traders were optimistic that prices would remain firm on
account of a lack of sufficient quality washed Arabica coffees in
the second half of the calendar year, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
"We can safely say that (Kenyan) coffee prices will remain
stable in the near future because there is a big demand for
Kenyan Coffee, normally used for blending," said Kenya Coffee
Board Public Relations Manager Paul Kivila.
</P>
<P>
Kenyans consume only around five percent of the 80,000-100,000
tons of coffee they produce. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970516.0139 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Regions Summit Debates on European Integration </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMSTERDAM, May 16 (Xinhua) -- Local and regional leaders and
representatives in the European Union (EU) today started
discussions how the regions and cities could better contribute to
the European integration.
</P>
<P>
The Summit of the Regions and Cities, opening on Thursday with
about 300 participants, was focused on issues of employment,
enlargement and the EU's institutional reform.
</P>
<P>
The meeting was held before leaders of the 15 EU member states
meet here in July to conclude the Intergovernmental Conference
(IGC) launched in March last year so as to revise the Maastricht
Treaty. 
</P>
