<DOCNO> XIE19970516.0140 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-16 10:33 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UAE Overcomes Deficit, Gains Surplus </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, May 16 (Xinhua) -- A surge in oil prices in 1996
enabled the United Arab Emirates (UAE) not onely overcome the
budget deficit, but also gained a markable surplus, an official
report said today.
</P>
<P>
The UAE had projected a deficit of some 241 million dollars in
its 1996 federal budget, but by the end of the year it recorded a
surplus of 973 million dollars, said a quarterly bulletin issued
by the UAE's Central Bank.
</P>
<P>
It is the highest surplus in the UAE federal budget since it
started to have the problem of deficit due to weak oil prices in
mid-1980s.
</P>
<P>
The report attributed the surplus to a surge in actual
revenues by more than 1.1 billion dollars to 5.62 billion
dollars, compared with some 4.5 billion dollars in 1995.
</P>
<P>
The surge came because of higher crude prices which soared by
about three dollars per barrel to an averaged 20 dollars in
1996.
</P>
<P>
The 1996 surplus was made in comparison with the actual budget
deficit of 256 million dollars in 1995, the reported showed.
</P>
<P>
The 1996 earnings included around 3.5 billion dollars in oil
income and the rest came from customs and corporate taxes, fees
on government services and return from overseas investment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
