<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Police Urged to Work Together Against Crime </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, May 16 (Xinhua) -- It was important that police
forces worldwide shared information in the fight against Asian
crime syndicates, said a Hong Kong detective who attended a
two-day crime seminar in Sydney this week.
</P>
<P>
"Asian crime had become very much an international, global
problem," Chief Superintendent of the Hong Kong Police Michael
Dowie was quoted by the Australian Associated Press today.
</P>
<P>
Around 140 police officers attended the sixth
multi-jurisdictional Asian crime seminar, which was addressed by
officers from Honk Kong, the United States and Australia.
</P>
<P>
Dowie said, "It is very important that we keep in touch with
other jurisdictions, because many of the Hong Kong criminals are
international criminals and they do have an influence in Australia
and in the U.S."
</P>
<P>
Crimes such as drug trafficking, credit card fraud, immigration
fraud, tax fraud and wildlife smuggling were discussed at the
seminar. The potential for Asian crime syndicates to operate in
Sydney during the 2000 Olympics was also talked about.
</P>
<P>
Superintendent Geoff Owens of the New South Wales Drug
Enforcement Agency told reporters that "there is a lot of
networking taking place at the seminar and that networking really
provided us with the opportunity to make contact with people
overseas and interstate, so that we can facilitate operations as
they come up".  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970516.0143 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ILO Threatens Nigeria With Sanction Over Human </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, May 16 (Xinhua) -- A more punitive measure is likely to
be taken by the International Labor Organization (ILO) against
Nigeria over its continued poor human rights record, the Guardian
reported today.
</P>
<P>
"The organization is now prepared to take a formal stand on
the human/trade rights situation in Nigerian, as we are becoming
more and more firm on international labor matters," Bert
Essenberg, director of ILO's regional office, said here on
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Although he was not categorical on what the country should
expect, the ILO official disclosed that the idea of setting up an
"ILO special commission of inquiry on the Nigerian situation is
already being floated by the governing council".
</P>
<P>
The Nigerian government recently ordered that trade unions in
the country are banned from international affiliation. This,
noted Essenberg, "goes contrary to general trend in Africa."
</P>
<P>
According to him, ILO has asked the Nigerian government to
explain why they took such a decision to which a reply is being
expected. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
