<DOCNO> XIE19970516.0144 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China, Japan, Kazakhstan Split Golds in Athletics </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PUSAN, May 16 (Xinhua) -- The trio of China, Japan and Kazakhstan
won three gold medals apiece with South Korea taking the remaining two
at the second-day athletics competitions at the East Asian Games here
on Friday.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese champions, each has a girl baby, were all veterans
including the eldest 30-year-old Li Tong in the Chinese squad, after
national runner-up Zhou Jing failed to notch up another gold for China
in the women's 100 meter hurdles.
</P>
<P>
Li Tong and Chen Yanhao finished one-two for China in the men's 110
meter hurdles by clocking in 13.67 and 13.70 seconds respectively.
Hisanobu Konae of Japan finished third in 13.85.
</P>
<P>
Li Tong, current Asian record holder who broke the marks 18 times,
said "we are strong in the discipline, and I alway win over teammate
Chen in international meets while he kept his clean slate against me
at home."
</P>
<P>
Zhang Lianbiao, 28, who ranked 11th in Atlanta Olympics, took the
javelin title with his second attempt of 77.80 meters, surpassing his
own games record of 77.56 set in Shanghai in 1993.
</P>
<P>
Toru Ue of Japan finished second in 73.74 while South Korean Kim
Ki-hun took the bronze medal in 72.42 meters.
</P>
<P>
Zhang who enjoyed a seven-year reign in the country and had his
best of 83.38 meters at the Hiroshima Asian Games in 1994, said
"because of the year-long injuries to my waist, I dared not to try my
best and had a medial performance here."
</P>
<P>
Jin Ling, Asian record holder of 1.97 meters set in 1989 Japan,
cleared 1.91 meters to take the women's high jump title, beating
Svetlana Zalevskaia of Kazakhstan to second in 1.88 meters who had her
personal best of 1.98 meters set in Pierae Benite, Russia in 1996.
</P>
<P>
"I skipped the attempts on 1.85 meters to prepare for tough
challenges in the later stages. I was not sure to win the gold medal,
but I was also not to surrender nothing without exerting my every
efforts," said the 1.83-meter slender mother athlete of a two-year-old
girl baby.
</P>
<P>
Japan won three gold medals through Yuka Mitsumori in the women's
10,000-meter walk, Yvonne Kanazawa in the women's 100-meter hurdles
and Yasunori Uchitomi in the men's 3,000-meter steeplechase.
</P>
<P>
Yuka clocked 46:23.25, beating Svetlana Tolstaia of Kazakhstan to
second with Chinese Feng Haixia bagging home the bronze medal in the
walk finals.
</P>
<P>
Yvonne finished first in the women's hurdles in 13.16, Chan
Sau-ying of Hong Kong ranked second in 13.29, with Chinese Liu Jing
ran her personal best of 13.31 for the bronze medal.
</P>
<P>
Yasunori led Wataru Izumi for a one-two finish for Japan in the
steeplechase with Chinese Qin Gang finished third.
</P>
<P>
Svetlana Bodritskaia awarded Kazakhstan its first gold medal in the
women's 400 meters by clocking in a new games record of 52.92, Chinese
Du Xiujie took the silver in 53.48 and Satomi Kasashima of Japan
returned with the bronze medal.
</P>
<P>
The other two golds for Kazakhstan were through Sergey Arzamassov
in the triple jump with a leap of 16.89 meters, and Sergey Rubtsov in
the men's shot put in a distance of 19.47 meters.
</P>
<P>
South Korean Son Ju-il sprinted ahead to take the men's 400 meters
title in 45.84, before compatriot Kim Tae-keun wound up the day's
competition to take the decathlon event with a total point of 7,372.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
