<HEADLINE> Ancient Temple Complex Found in Cambodia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PHNOM PENH, May 16 (Xinhua) -- Archeologists have discovered an
ancient temple complex near the world-renown Angkor Wat in the
northern part of Cambodia, press reports said here today.
</P>
<P>
The 13th century architecture, known as Prasat Banteay, sits in
the deep forest about three kilometers northwest of the famous
Angkor Thom temple complex in Siem Reap Province.
</P>
<P>
Considered high of historic value, the newly-discovered complex
is composed of three finely carved stone structures and bears
resemblance to the Bayon temple at Angkor Thom.
</P>
<P>
Archeologists said the archeological site is well preserved
except that some Buddha statues have been stolen.
</P>
<P>
The Cambodian government is reportedly planning to repair the
complex and construct a road linking it with Angkor Thom, so as to
attract more tourists. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970516.0150 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese NPC Chairman Meets French President </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 16 (Xinhua) -- Qiao Shi, chairman of the Standing
Committee of the Chinese National People's Congress (NPC), told
visiting French President Jacques Chirac earlier today that his
China trip will open a new chapter in Sino-French relations.
</P>
<P>
Extending a warm welcome to President Chirac, Qiao recalled his
successful visit to France at the end of March this year, and
expressed his heart-felt thanks for the warm reception he received
during that visit from Chirac, the French parliament, and
government leaders.
</P>
<P>
Qiao said President Chirac's current visit to China is a great
event in bilateral relations, and that the presidents of both
sides have conducted cordial and friendly talks.
</P>
<P>
Qiao voiced his conviction that the president's current visit
will surely be crowned with a success, and further push forward
the development of Sino-French friendship and cooperation.
</P>
<P>
During the past few years, Qiao said, Sino-French ties have
maintained a good momentum for development with the attention and
efforts of leaders of both countries including President Chirac.
</P>
<P>
Bilateral friendly cooperation in various aspects including
politics, economy, science and technology, and culture have
continuously developed, and there have been a constant exchange of
visits between leaders of the two sides, noted Qiao, adding that
leaders of the two parliaments have also been in friendly contract.
</P>
<P>
Qiao said the Sino-French Joint Declaration, which was signed
here today between Chinese President Jiang Zemin and his French
counterpart Chirac, summarized the consensus of the two countries
on major issues facing the world today, and indicated their
aspiration and determination to establish a comprehensive
partnership for the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
Qiao called the Declaration an important document guiding
bilateral relations, saying that it will bring Sino-French ties
into a new era of development.
</P>
<P>
China is ready to make joint efforts together with the French
side to cooperate more closely to promote the growth of the trend
in the world's multi-polarization and the economic growth of all
countries, to the benefit of humanity, Qiao said.
</P>
<P>
Noting that his visit here is smooth and fruitful, President
Chirac said the joint declaration signed just before his meeting
with Qiao signifies that France-China relations have entered into
a new period.
</P>
<P>
President Chirac went on to say that the world is undergoing
dramatic changes and the development of world situation demands
for a strengthening of cooperation between France and China, and
between Europe and China.
</P>
<P>
Both agreed to further increase exchanges and contacts between
parliaments of the two countries, so as to enhance the mutual
understandings and friendly cooperation between the two peoples.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, President Chirac conveyed greetings to Qiao
from Philippe Seguin, president of the French National Assembly,
and Rene Monory, president of the French Senate.
</P>
<P>
Expressing his thanks, Qiao asked President Chirac to convey
his regards to Seguin and Monory. 
</P>
</TEXT>
