<HEADLINE> Manila Stocks Plunge for Second Day </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, May 16 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine Stock Exchange index
fell for the second day today amid rising fears that the peso
would suffer the same fate as Thailand's battered baht.
</P>
<P>
The composite index, which lost 75 points Thursday, closed down
54.96 points today at 2,576.13 while the turnover totaled 5.5
billion shares with a value of 83 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said Thailand's financial woes had spilled over to
other regional currencies including the Philippine peso,
triggering heavy selling pressure and sending Asia's main bourses
to plunge.
</P>
<P>
In Thailand itself, the share prices tumbled 4.2 percent at
Thursday morning session after the baht plunged in European trade
to a 10-year low.
</P>
<P>
To defend the peso, the Philippine Central Bank Thursday raised
its overnight borrowing rate by 0.75 percentage points to 12
percent and dumped some 70 million U.S. dollars to buy at the rate
of 1:26.375.
</P>
<P>
The Philippine Stock Market just enjoyed a transient recovery
from continued plunges starting from the end of last month to
early this month. 
</P>
</TEXT>
