<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ILO Threatens Nigeria With Sanction Over Human </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, May 16 (Xinhua) -- A more punitive measure is likely to
be taken by the International Labor Organization (ILO) against
Nigeria over its continued poor human rights record, the Guardian
reported today.
</P>
<P>
"The organization is now prepared to take a formal stand on
the human/trade rights situation in Nigerian, as we are becoming
more and more firm on international labor matters," Bert
Essenberg, director of ILO's regional office, said here on
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Although he was not categorical on what the country should
expect, the ILO official disclosed that the idea of setting up an
"ILO special commission of inquiry on the Nigerian situation is
already being floated by the governing council".
</P>
<P>
The Nigerian government recently ordered that trade unions in
the country are banned from international affiliation. This,
noted Essenberg, "goes contrary to general trend in Africa."
</P>
<P>
According to him, ILO has asked the Nigerian government to
explain why they took such a decision to which a reply is being
expected. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
