<DOCNO> XIE19970516.0155 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia Obtains Strong Trade Surplus for March 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, May 16 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia's external trade
surplus for March increased 375.3 percent over that in the
preceding month due to higher exports and lower imports, according
to the Statistics Department today.
</P>
<P>
The trade figures released by the department today show that
Malaysia recorded a surplus of 1.751 billion ringgit (over 700
million U.S. dollars) in March compared with the surplus of 368.5
million ringgit (about 147.4 million U.S. dollars) for February.
</P>
<P>
The country recorded a trade deficit of 102.9 million ringgit
(about 41.16 million U.S. dollars) in January.
</P>
<P>
The improved showing was due to the combined results of higher
exports, which increased 2.8 percent to 18.680 billion ringgit
(about 7.472 billion U. S. dollars) and lower imports, which
showed a drop of 4.1 percent to 16.929 billion ringgit (about
6.7716 billion U.S. dollars), the department said.
</P>
<P>
As for the January-March period this year, Malaysia recorded a
trade surplus of 2.016 billion ringgit (about 806.4 million U.S.
dollars) compared with a deficit of 1.357 billion ringgit (about
542.8 million U.S. dollars) during the same 1996 period, according
to the department.
</P>
<P>
During the first quarter of 1997, Malaysia's exports rose 3.5
percent to 48.956 billion ringgit (about 19.5824 billion U.S.
dollars) while its imports showed a drop of 3.5 percent to 46.939
billion ringgit (about 18.7756 billion U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Malaysia's exports during the corresponding 1996 period totaled
47.309 billion ringgit (about 18.9236 billion U.S. dollars) while
imports in the same period totaled 48.666 billion ringgit (about
19.4664 billion U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
In the first three months of this year, thermionic valves and
tubes, photocells and parts continued to be the major source of
revenue, with their receipts amounting to 18.9 percent of the
total exports.
</P>
<P>
Palm oil was the next most important foreign exchange earner,
accounting for 4.3 percent of the total exports.
</P>
<P>
The department said the other products which recorded strong
export increases in the first quarter were liquefied natural gas,
plain plywood, petroleum products and pepper.
</P>
<P>
However, there were big decreases in the exports of rubber,
sawn timber, palm kernel cake and palm kernel oil.
</P>
<P>
As for imports, machinery and transport equipment represented
58.4 percent of the total imports during the first three months
when "lumpy" imports comprising ships, boats and floating
structures, aircraft and associated equipment, fell a whopping
44.4 percent from total imports of 2.2 billion ringgit (about 880
million U.S. dollars) during the same period of 1996.
</P>
<P>
The major import components under the machinery and transport
equipment sector which showed strong increases were automatic data
processing machines and units, heating and cooling equipment
parts, parts and accessories for office machines and automatic
data processing equipment.
</P>
<P>
Others included taps, cocks, valves and similar appliances and
steam or other vapor generating boilers, superheated water boilers
and auxiliary plants and parts.
</P>
<P>
During the first quarter, Malaysia's major trading partners
were Japan, Singapore, the United States, South Korea, Thailand,
Hong Kong, Germany and the United Kingdom, which combined to
account for 75.5 percent of the total trade value.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
