<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ghana Joins Race for West Africa Load Center </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, May 16 (Xinhua) -- Ghana has joined Nigeria, Cote
d'Ivoire, Gambia and Togo in bidding for the World Bank's West
Africa Load Center, the "Nigerian Tribune" reported today.
</P>
<P>
Director-general of Ghana Ports and Harbors, Kwaku Dolvo
confirmed his country's interests during a recent visit to the
Tincan-Island Port in Lagos, the newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
"Ghana is a smaller country, compared with Nigeria, and our
ports are smaller too. But we have very good facilities," Dolvo
reportedly said.
</P>
<P>
He added that every country with a port is likely to show deep
interest in the World Bank's gesture, because of its tremendous
economic potentials.
</P>
<P>
While answering reporters' questions after his visit, Dolvo
observed that Nigeria has the best natural ports in Africa, but
he also remarked Nigerian ports are not fully equipped with the
most relevant time-saving plants and equipment.
</P>
<P>
As to the ship turn around, Dolvo said Abidjan may have an
edge over Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
Nigeria and Cote d'Ivoire are widely regarded as the most
competitive candidates in the race for the World Bank's load
center, which is likely to have a great impact in the port and
shipping industry in the sub-region. 
</P>
</TEXT>
