<HEADLINE> S'pore's Manufacturing Output Falls in March </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, May 16 (Xinhua) -- Singapore's total manufacturing
output fell 8.5 percent in March this year, compared to a year
ago, as a result of reduced output from a broad spectrum of
industries, the government Economic Development Board (EDB) said
today.
</P>
<P>
The output of the electronics industry declined in March 12.4
percent year-on-year, the EDB said, adding that higher output in
the disk drives, telecommunication equipment and personal
computers segment was more than offset by the declines in the
semiconductor, consumer electronics and other electronics
segments.
</P>
<P>
The electronics industry's decline led to the slowdown in the
fabricated metal, rubber and plastic products industries, it said,
adding that declines of 11.6 percent and 18.2 percent were
recorded in the segments respectively.
</P>
<P>
The chemical industries declined 5.2 percent due to reduced
production in petroleum and petrochemical segments, while the
output of the petroleum products fell 16.6 percent as two major
refineries shut down their plants for maintenance during the
month, and the output of petrochemical products dropped 9.7
percent.
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, the output of food and beverages declined 13.8
percent with less export orders and keen competition from imports
contributed to a lower output, the EDB said.
</P>
<P>
The transport equipment industry seemed to be the brightest
spot as it grew 3.3 percent mainly because of higher output in the
aviation segment where overseas contracts continued to boost the
repair services and the manufacture of aircraft parts.  
</P>
</TEXT>
