<HEADLINE> Israeli Warplanes Strikes Lebanese Guerrilla </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, May 16 (Xinhua) -- Israeli warplanes carried out this
morning four consecutive air raids at guerrilla bases of the
pro-Iranian Hezbollah, or Party of God, in south Lebanon, but
there was not immediate report on casualties.
</P>
<P>
The warplanes fired eight air-to-surface missiles at targets
on the hill of Telal Al-Dhahr in Western Beqaa, some 85
kilometers southeast of the Lebanese capital Beirut, security
sources in the area said.
</P>
<P>
The air raids came several hours following a violent clash
between Hezbollah fighters and Israeli commandos near Telal
Al-Dhahr over the night.
</P>
<P>
Israeli army admitted that in the fighting, which lasted from
9:00 p.m. (1800 GMT) until 0:10 a.m. (2100 GMT), three Israeli
soldiers were killed and seven others wounded, the worst loss
for the 1,000-strong Israeli occupation forces in a single clash
since this year.
</P>
<P>
The fighting erupted when the Hezbollah militants spotted the
Israeli commandos attempting to infiltrate out of the
Israeli-occupied border strip and showered over the hill upon
them with various weapons.
</P>
<P>
Security sources said one guerrilla was killed, but the
Muslim Shiite fundamentalist organization denied any casualties
among its fighters.
</P>
<P>
The clash added to nine killed and 40 others injured the
Israeli casualties in south Lebanon since this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
