<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Foreign Ministry Announcement on Visa to HK </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 16 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese Foreign Ministry issued
an announcement concerning visa applications to Hong Kong today.
</P>
<P>
The full text of the announcement reads as follows:
</P>
<P>
After the resumption by the Government of the People's Republic
of China of the exercise of sovereignty over Hong Kong on July 1,
1997, those people from other countries or some regions who will
come to the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (HKSAR) as a
tourist or for short business trips and who are currently enjoying
visa-free access to Hong Kong will, in principle, continue to
enjoy this status, as a measure to facilitate personnel exchanges
between the HKSAR and the countries or regions. In accordance with
the provisions of Article 154 of the Basic Law, "the Government of
the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region may apply immigration
controls on entry into, stay in and departure from the Region by
persons from foreign states and regions", a list of the countries
and regions to enjoy the visa exemption treatment and the specific
measures concerning the granting of the visa exemption shall be
decided upon and made public by the Government of the Hong Kong
Special Administrative Region.
</P>
<P>
All foreigners shall apply for visas and go through the
necessary formalities in accordance with the relevant regulations
in force at the present as they do now if they wish to travel to
other parts of China.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese side is working at a transitional arrangement for
the visas for entry into Hong Kong issued by the British Hong Kong
Government, and how to process the visa applications for entry
into Hong Kong by China's diplomatic missions and consular posts
abroad which will be made public once worked out. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
