<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Lake Victoria Threatened by Over-fishing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, May 16 (Xinhua) -- Lake Victoria, the second largest
fresh water lake in the world, has been threatened by
over-fishing in recent years.
</P>
<P>
According to a latest report from Uganda Fisheries and Fish
Conservation Association, the total fleet of fishing boats along
the shores of the lake in the country rose from 11,000 in 1970s
to 20,000 by late 1980, involving about 100,000 people.
</P>
<P>
And the number of unregistered boats is also very high, the
report said, adding that this has put a lot of strain on the fish
stocks.
</P>
<P>
In another development, fish processing industries have
sprouted in the last six years. By last year, 12 companies, all
located on the shores of the lake, were operational. Fourteen
other companies have been licensed, of which several are under
construction.
</P>
<P>
All these companies rely on Nile perch which was introduced
into the lake in the 1950s. Their production is mainly of chilled
and frozen fish, of which about 90 percent is exported into the
European Union countries, Israel, North America, and Southeast
Asia.
</P>
<P>
Due to the increase of fish processing factories, the
country's fish exports increased from 6,238 tons in 1993 to 6,650
tons in 1994 and 7,000 tons in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Nevertheless, the figures above do not include exports of
smoked and salted fish of mainly Nile perch by small traders to
Zaire, Rwanda and Kenya.
</P>
<P>
Installed production capacity of these fish plants in Uganda
was estimated at 73,000 tons of raw fish per year.
</P>
<P>
Due to the increase of fish processing factories, they are not
only consuming a lot of fish, but also have been encouraging the
catching of immature Nile perch.
</P>
<P>
Fishermen have thus narrowed the mesh of their fish nets from
five inches recommended for the lake to three even two inches for
catching more fishes including immature fishes.
</P>
<P>
Because of this situation, annual fish production in the whole
country decreased from 276,000 tons in 1993 to 213,000 tons in
1994 and 220,000 tons in 1995 respectively. It is estimated that
Lake Victoria provides a half of these figures above.
</P>
<P>
Experts here attributed this situation to the current number
of factories which is more than three times the number
recommended by a marine study carried out at the beginning of
this decade.
</P>
<P>
In short, the experts hold that it is disregard of the
available exploitable resources that has caused over exploitation
of fish in the lake.
</P>
<P>
However, there is still a way out. That is to develop proper
fishing gear and deep fishing methods in the lake with a total
area of 68,000 square kilometers, because though small Nile perch
is being over fished, the giant ones are not being caught.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970516.0178 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-16 </DATE_TIME>
