<HEADLINE> Chinese Veterans Wins Three Golds At Track and Field </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PUSAN, May 16 (Xinhua) -- Chinese veterans took home three out of
11 gold medals at stake on Friday at the second Pusan East Asian
Games.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese trio, with a girl baby each, became the lone champions
for China at the second-day athletics competitions.
</P>
<P>
Zhang Lianbiao, 28, who ranked 11th in Atlanta Olympics, threw the
javelin in his second attempt to a winning distance of 77.80 meters,
surpassing his own games record of 77.56 set in Shanghai in 1993.
</P>
<P>
Toru Ue of Japan finished second in 73.74 while South Korean Kim
Ki-hun took the bronze medal in 72.42 meters.
</P>
<P>
Zhang who enjoyed a seven-year reign in the country, said "because
of the year-long injuries to my waist, I dared not to try my best and
had a medial performance here."
</P>
<P>
Zhang recorded his best of 83.38 meters at the Hiroshima Asian
Games in 1994, and took the javelin title from the Fukuoka Universiade
in 79.06 meters.
</P>
<P>
Jin Ling, Asian record holder of 1.97 meters set in 1989 in
Hannaamatsu of Japan, cleared 1.91 meters to take the women's high
jump title, beating Svetlana Zalevskaia of Kazakhstan to second in
1.88 meters who had her personal best of 1.98 meters set in Pierae
Benite, Russia in 1996.
</P>
<P>
"I skipped the attempts on 1.85 meters to prepare for tough
challenges in the later stage because she (Svetlana) had the better
performance of 1.95 meters this year," said Jin Ling of Da Lian, an
eastern port city.
</P>
<P>
"My best of 1.93 meters of the year was set in February at the
Beijing Sino-Japanese Athletics Contest, I was not sure to win the
gold gold, but I was also not to surrender nothing without exerting my
every efforts," said the 1.83-meter Chinese slender, mother athlete of
a girl child of two years.
</P>
<P>
Li Tong and Chen Yanhao finished one-two for China in the men's 110
meter hurdles by clocking in 13.67 and 13.70 seconds respectively.
Hisanobu Konae of Japan finished third in 13.85.
</P>
<P>
Li Tong, the oldest runner in the Chinese squad who celebrated his
30th birthday on May 6th, said "We are strong in the discipline, and I
alway win over teammate Chen in international meets while he kept his
clean slate against me at home."
</P>
<P>
"Actually, I'm not satisfied with my performance today, and Chen
may become the champion should he not kick on the eighth hurdle," said
the Asian record holder of 13.25 set in Linz, Austria in 1994.
</P>
<P>
Li Tong, father of a year-old girl baby, had broken the Asian
records 18 times with the first-ever feat recorded in 1989 when he
clocked 13.68 seconds to surpass the previous mark of 13.72 seconds.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
