<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Huge Foreign Exchange Siphoned out of Kenya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, May 16 (Xinhua) -- Some internationally registered
firms are being siphoning Kenya's foreign exchange to western
countries under the cover of international business, the Kenya
Times reported today.
</P>
<P>
The paper said that the Central Bank of Kenya (CBK) had
confirmed the existence of the scheme involving a colossal
amounts of foreign exchange in the wake of economic
liberalization.
</P>
<P>
Last Monday, the CBK investigators learnt of a racket by two
Nairobi-based businessmen who had fled the country with over 30
million Dollars.
</P>
<P>
A press statement issued by the CBK said that a certain
director in one commercial bank was said to have obtained about
370,000 U.S. Dollars from a financial institution on the basis of
forged promissory notes.
</P>
<P>
The paper noted that the said director similarly obtained from
six local banks a total of about 9 million Dollars through a
motor vehicle firm in which he is said to be a director.
</P>
<P>
Kenyan police spokesman Peter Kimanthi told the paper that
police had launched thorough investigations with a view to
uncovering the rackets and were awaiting tangible evidence to
pursue the fraud.
</P>
<P>
The paper pointed out that the dirty tricks being employed in
the schemes involve political conspiracy, blackmail and corruption
and were hampering the CBK's investigations.
</P>
<P>
A senior opposition leader and two business executives are
said to be directly involved in the recent racket, the paper
added.
</P>
<P>
The investigations by the CBK came as a result of complaints
by some local banks who complained of abuse of the Import
Declaration Forms (IDF) by a locally-registered firm called
Specialized Lighting System (SLS).
</P>
<P>
The SLS has their orders for goods canceled but the money
they had collected from Kenya in IDF is being retained in a
London bank.
</P>
<P>
The CBK boss Joseph Kamau has confirmed that SLS was being
investigated, said the paper, adding that the flagrant use of IDF
for fictitious business deals was far too common. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
