<HEADLINE> Chinese, French Presidents Meet in Beijing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 16 (Xinhua) -- Chinese President Jiang Zemin met
with visiting French President Jacques Chirac in Zhongnanhai here
today, exchanging views on international issues of concern.
</P>
<P>
This is the second meeting between the two leaders following
yesterday's official talks.
</P>
<P>
Describing the talks as "in-depth, friendly, frank, and
fruitful", Jiang said both sides signed a series of agreements
between the two governments, some important business contracts and
letters of intent yesterday, and will sign, after the meeting, the
Sino-French Joint Declaration, which, he said, is a very important
document.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, he said, the current visit by Chirac has scored
substantive results in the political, economic, and trade sectors.
</P>
<P>
Jiang briefed Chirac on China's views on the Asian situation,
and on the Sino-Russian and Sino-U.S. relations, while Chirac
introduced the situation in Europe, the EU integration, and NATO's
planned eastward expansion.
</P>
<P>
Both sides agreed that Asia will rise abruptly, Europe will
continue to develop, and there exists great potential for
strengthening Asia-Europe cooperation, which are all conducive to
the development of the world's multi-polarization.
</P>
<P>
They also reached consensus on strengthening consultations on
international issues.
</P>
<P>
Jiang stated that China and France have no conflicts involving
fundamental interests. Instead they share identical or similar
views on major international issues.
</P>
<P>
Under the new international circumstances, Jiang said, the
common grounds shared by the two countries have not reduced, but
increased.
</P>
<P>
Jiang noted that the common views, shared from a strategic
height, on the orientation and characteristics of the
international situation and principles of handling international
issues, have been recorded in the Sino-French Joint Declaration.
</P>
<P>
This not only serves as important guidelines for the future
bilateral relations, but will also exert great and far-reaching
impact in the international arena, Jiang said.
</P>
<P>
Chirac said he was convinced that his current visit is an
important step for the development of the France-China relations
in the right direction.
</P>
<P>
The two presidents agreed that leaders of the two countries
increase contacts, and continue their fruitful dialogue and
consultations on international issues and the UN affairs.
</P>
<P>
Chirac invited Jiang to visit France again, for which Jiang
expressed thanks and accepted with pleasure.
</P>
<P>
After the meeting, the two leaders signed the Sino-French Joint
Declaration.
</P>
<P>
Present at the meeting were Chinese Vice-Premier and Foreign
Minister Qian Qichen, Head of the Chinese Government Reception
Committee and Minister in charge of the State Economic and Trade
Commission Wang Zhongyu, Minister in charge of the State Planning
Commission Chen Jinhua, and French Foreign Minister Herve De
Charette.
</P>
<P>
Prior to the meeting, Chirac presented Jiang with an original
certificate that late Chinese leader Deng Xiaoping used when he
was on a work-study program in France in 1921.
</P>
<P>
Jiang expressed his great thanks for it. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
