<DOCNO> XIE19970516.0199 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Coastal Areas Step Up Oceanic Development </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANGZHOU, May 16 (Xinhua) -- East China's Zhejiang Province,
which has the longest coastal line in the country, plans to set up
a special fund for oceanic development within the year.
</P>
<P>
Provincial officials hope that foreign investors will have
interest in the oceanic projects.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, mapping out regulations to protect and
develop oceanic resources is also progressing.
</P>
<P>
Besides Zhejiang, all the coastal provinces and cities in China
have worked out their plans to develop and protect the oceanic
resources.
</P>
<P>
China has a coastal line of 18,000 km and a sea area of more
than three million sq km. The output value of China's oceanic
industry accounts for four percent of the national gross product;
the figure for developed nations is about 20 percent.
</P>
<P>
Chinese officials have attached great importance to the oceanic
industry. All the coastal provinces and cities have set up organs
in charge of marine affairs. To promote the oceanic resources
development, the provinces and cities have improved the
construction of infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
Zhejiang has decided to give priority to eight areas in
developing oceanic resources: salt water cultivation and high-sea
fishing, petroleum and gas development, oceanic engineering, usage
of salt water, marine biological engineering, oceanic energy
resources, disaster relief, and remote sensing technology
application. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
