<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dhaka Stock Exchange Ends Week Higher </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Dhaka, May 16 (Xinhua) -- Trading on the floor of the Dhaka
Stock Exchange (DSE) registered a significant rise as the
investors responded positively to the changes in the DSE Council
including its chairman.
</P>
<P>
The price index, the barometer of the stock prices, reached
1144.58 points Thursday, 82.36 points higher than the previous
week's closing of 1062.22.
</P>
<P>
Turnover increased remarkably last week as the bourse
experienced a balanced trading when both sellers and buyers were
active. Of the listed 212 issues, 136 changed hands at the
valedictory session which was highest in terms of transacted
issues so far this year.
</P>
<P>
However, prices of the traded issues fluctuated during the
period. Most of the issues posted rise, some issues incurred
marginal loss and some issues remained unchanged.
</P>
<P>
The traditional market leader Beximco Pharma was the major
gainer of the week as the issue registered a gain of about 54 Taka
(about 1.3 U.S. dollars) per share on speculative buying. There
was speculations in the market that Beximco Pharma would declare
healthy dividends and bonus shares soon.
</P>
<P>
The other major gainers of the week were ALCL (Pran), Quasem
Drycells, Shine Pukur Holsing, Olympic Industries, Padma Textile
and BTC.
</P>
<P>
In contrast, Bangas Limited, Lonon Jute Stafflers and Lodern
Dyeing incurred losses. Besides, prices of the issues in the
textile sector remained almost static last week.
</P>
<P>
The investors regained their confidence in the capital market
as a new face took over the DSE leadership from Imtiyaz Hussain,
who was accused of share market manipulation.
</P>
<P>
The DSE Council Sunday removed its chairman Imtiyaz in a
no-confidence motion and elected MA Hug Howlader as the new
chairman. As a result, the market witnessed lively trading last
week, brokers said.
</P>
<P>
However, some brokers apprehended that the share prices would
tumble again as the former DSE chairman was planning to challenge
his removal in the court. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
