<DOCNO> XIE19970516.0209 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Singapore Economy Up 3.8 Percent in First Quarter </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, May 16 (Xinhua) -- The Singapore economy grew 3.8
percent in the first quarter of this year amid mixed growth
performance, the Ministry for Trade and Industry announced today
when publishing the economic survey of the first quarter 1997.
</P>
<P>
The manufacturing sector shrank 6.7 percent, down further from
0.7 percent a quarter earlier due to weak electronics demand,
while all major industries, except for chemicals, declined during
the quarter, it said.
</P>
<P>
The ministry noted that apart from disk drives and
telecommunications equipment, other electronics segments such as
personal computers, consumer electronics and semiconductors
remained weak.
</P>
<P>
The non-electronics segments performed weakly due to structural
and industry-specific factors, it said, adding that growth in the
petroleum industry was affected by plant shutdowns while printing
and publishing continued to face keen competition. The only bright
spot was chemicals due to increased capacity coming on stream.
</P>
<P>
The financial and business services sector grew 10.5 percent,
up from ten percent a quarter earlier. Domestic credit remained
healthy, while business services continued to perform strongly,
expanding 8.4 percent on the back of strong information technology
and headquarters activities.
</P>
<P>
Commerce sector growth slowed to three percent. Entrepot trade
was dampened by sluggish regional growth and weak electronics
demand. The retail sub-sector remained affected by structural
factors, with sales growing 0.6 percent as a result that only
selected segments like furniture and clothing received a boost
from festive spending.
</P>
<P>
The survey also showed that transport and communications growth
was healthy at 7.6 percent in the first quarter, as the
communications sub-sector benefited from impending liberalization
of the mobile telecommunications market.
</P>
<P>
In addition, despite the cooling property market, construction
growth remained healthy at 10.7 percent. The survey showed that
though contracts awarded in the first quarter of this year
declined 1.6 percent to 3.7 billion Singapore dollars (about 2.55
billion U.S. dollars), public-sector demand, especially in
residential activity, remained strong. Total contracts awarded are
expected to reach 18 billion Singapore dollars (about 12.41
billion U.S. dollars) this year, a bit lower than 1996.  
</P>
</TEXT>
