JOHANNESBURG, May 16 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news
items in leading South African newspapers today.
</P>
<P>
The Citizen
</P>
<P>
-- Chief Executive Officer of the Independent Broadcasting
Authority (IBA), Harris Gxaweni, was suspended with immediate
effect on Thursday night and five of the seven IBA councillors
announced their resignation, following a damning report by the
auditor-general on financial mismanagement and fraud within the
IBA.
</P>
<P>
-- Former Pan Africanist Congress president Clarence Makwetu,
who was recently expelled by the party's Internal Disciplinary
Committee for dividing the party, creating factions and breaking
his oath of allegiance, will keep his seat in parliament until
the party's National Executive Committee meets on May 24 to
decide his fate.
</P>
<P>
The Star
</P>
<P>
-- President Nelson Mandela told a media briefing after talks
with Zairean rebel leader Laurent Kabila at his official Cape
Town residence on Thursday night that Zairean President Mobutu
Sese Seko wanted four days' grace to study South African
proposals for peaceful handover of power to the rebels waiting at
the gate of the capital Kinsasha. 
