<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Pushes County-Level Economic Reform </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANGZHOU, May 16 (Xinhua) -- Comprehensive reform at China's
county-level is an important component of building the socialist
market economic system.
</P>
<P>
This view was shared by over 200 Chinese officials, economists
and scholars attending a national seminar on economic reform in
counties, which opened Thursday at Yiwu City in east China's
Zhejiang Province.
</P>
<P>
Official statistics showed that over 80 percent of the
population in China live in counties. Last year, 60 percent of the
country's gross domestic product (GDP) and half of the commodity
retail sales came from counties.
</P>
<P>
At present, the industrial output yielded by counties across
the country makes up half of China's total. Workers on the
payrolls of rural enterprises in counties surpassed the number
employed by the state-owned enterprises in the country, said Gao
Shangquan, vice-president of the China Society for Research on the
Economic Restructuring.
</P>
<P>
Economic growth at the county level will define national
economic development and is the basis of social and political
stability in China, he noted.
</P>
<P>
However, Gao stated, that the majority of counties are facing
such problems like overstaffed government institutions, irrational
economic structure, some 50 percent of the counties need financial
allowance, nearly 60 million people still do not have adequate
food and clothing, and the gap between the counties in the western
and eastern regions is widening. "In-depth reform is the only way
to solve these problems," participants said.
</P>
<P>
Experts called on all counties to speed up the integration of
urban and rural development and diversify the rural economy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
