<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hebei Seeks 3.5 Billion-Dollar Loan from Overseas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHIJIAZHUANG, May 16 (Xinhua) -- North China's Hebei Province
intends to borrow 3.5 billion US dollars from international
financial organizations and foreign governments by the year 2000,
according to a senior provincial official.
</P>
<P>
The loans will be used to finance more than 60 projects
scheduled for the 1996-2000 period and feasibility studies,
executive vice-governor Cong Fukui said.
</P>
<P>
Some of the projects, such as those concerning water supply in
the rural and urban areas, environmental protection, and
afforestation in poverty-ridden areas, will be covered by loans
from the World Bank, he said.
</P>
<P>
Lendings by the Asian Development Bank will be pumped into a
power plant and part of the Beijing-Shanghai expressway that runs
through Hebei, the official added.
</P>
<P>
The province is also seeking loans from the World Bank and foreign
governments to finance the construction of road systems around the
provincial capital and a number of other projects, Cong said.
</P>
<P>
Cong said that Hebei has since the 1980s implemented a total of
181 projects funded by overseas loans, with the combined amount
reaching 1.5 billion US dollars, 30 percent of the total
investment used by the province.
</P>
<P>
"The loans have to some extent eased our province's fund
shortage and helped accelerate construction of a large number of
key projects," he said.
</P>
<P>
The projects supported by overseas loans have played a positive
role in helping Hebei improve its infrastructure, basic
industries, and ecology, Cong noted.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
