<DOCNO> XIE19970516.0220 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S'pore Gov't Keeps 1997 Growth Forecast of 5-7 Pct </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, May 16 (Xinhua) -- The Singapore government said
today that it retains its earlier 1997 economic growth forecast of
five to seven percent, though the country's economy grew 3.8
percent in the first quarter of the year.
</P>
<P>
In releasing the Economic Survey for the first quarter 1997,
the Ministry of Trade and Industry said that the slower growth
scored in the first quarter was due mainly to the decline in the
manufacturing sector.
</P>
<P>
"Electronics and electronics-related industries remained weak
as a result of the slowdown in global electronics demand. Entrepot
trade and the transport sub-sectors were similarly affected," it
noted.
</P>
<P>
However, the ministry said that on the external front, the
growth outlook for industrialized and regional countries remained
healthy. The United States is likely to remain strong, it said,
adding that the European Union is expected to continue its
recovery while Japan will grow more slowly than in 1996.
</P>
<P>
It also noted that there are some signs of a pickup in global
electronics demand, with stronger demand for electronics
components and continued inventory adjustments in the United
States. Industry analysts are also generally optimistic about a
global recovery in semiconductors demand, the ministry said.
</P>
<P>
Domestically, forward-looking indicators like the Composite
Leading Index and business expectations remain generally
favorable, while business expectations for manufacturing have
become more positive, with selected electronics and chemicals
manufacturers expecting better business, the ministry noted.
</P>
<P>
However, it also warned that the recovery of the various
components is likely to be uneven, and the pace and timing of the
recovery also remain uncertain.
</P>
<P>
"Taking all these factors into consideration, the Ministry of
Trade and Industry retains its earlier 1997 growth forecast of
five to seven percent," it said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
