<HEADLINE> Fish Canning Firms Rush to Zanzibar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, May 16 (Xinhua) -- Five fishing companies have
proposed a total investment of 13.7 billion Tanzania Shillings
(about 22.8 million US Dollars) in Zanzibar's fisheries industry,
local press reported today.
</P>
<P>
The Director General of Zanzibar Investment Agency, Hemed
Hikmany told reporters in the town of Zanzibar on Thursday that
the proposed ventures could have taken off earlier if a wrangle
over the territorial boundary between Zanzibar and Tanzania
Mainland was not the obstacle.
</P>
<P>
The two sides have reached a compromise over the border and
foreign owned as well as locally based companies may soon start
fishing and canning their catches, he said.
</P>
<P>
According to Hikmany, Africa Fishing Company which has leased
premises and equipment from Zanzibar Fishing Corporation would go
to sea before the end of May.
</P>
<P>
Oman-based fishing firm, Asmak Oman, which had set up an
office in Zanzibar in 1992 and pulled out a year later, has
decided to return and install fish storage facilites at different
locations around Zanzibar and Pemba isllands.
</P>
<P>
Hikmany said Zanzibaris who have grown up by the sea, will
find employment and business opportunites in three other
companies, namely, Sea Fisheries, Ocean Seafood of Bumbwini
Makoba in North Zanzibar, and South Africa-based Fish shipping
Agency. 
</P>
</TEXT>
