<HEADLINE> Same Budget Day Agreed for East Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, May 16 (Xinhua) -- Kenya, Tanzania and Uganda
have agreed to revert to a common budget day in order to allow
smooth implementation of policy decisions which need the
co-operation of the three countries, local press reported today.
</P>
<P>
Following the agreement, ministers of finance of the three
countries will announce budget proposals for the next financial
year in their respective parliaments on June 12.
</P>
<P>
Within the framework of the East African Co-operation (EAC),
the partner states have outlined specific areas for common action
in order to enhance economic integration of the region.
</P>
<P>
Kenya and Uganda are scheduled to unveil the budgets on June
12, but Tanzania was looking on the possibility of rescheduling
its budget day from June 19 to coincide with its partners in the
EAC.
</P>
<P>
Speaker of the Tanzanian National Assembly, Pius Msekwa, told
the official "Daily News" recently that the decision to have a
common budget day was reached by the EAC Authority, during the
summit held in Arusha, northern Tanzania recently.
</P>
<P>
He said the move was in line with the spirit of strengthening
co-operation in East Africa.
</P>
<P>
Until the collapse of the East African Community in 1977, the
three countries unveiled their budgets at the same day. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
