<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-16 06:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 8 Israeli Casualties Reported in S. Lebanon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, May 16 (Xinhua) -- There were eight Israeli
casualties in overnight heavy fighting in South Lebanon between
Hezbollah forces and Israeli troops, local media reported today.
</P>
<P>
The Hebrew daily Haaretz reported that heavy fighting occurred
around the northeastern sector of the south Lebanon security
zone when a group of Israeli soldiers were ambushed by Hezbollah
gunmen. It said there were at least eight Israeli casualties in
the fighting, but this has not been officially confirmed.
</P>
<P>
The fighting erupted around 9 p.m. Thursday night in the
Zumriyya area and continued after midnight. Israel retaliated
with heavy air and artillery bombardments of the area, with over
350 shells being fired within two hours, Israel Radio and
televisions reported without giving the number of casualties.
</P>
<P>
Thursday's fighting signaled the escalation of clashes
between the two sides. It was apparently an act of retaliation
launched by Hezbollah which lost four fighters on Monday in a
failed attempt to capture a position held by the pro-Israeli
South Lebanese Army in the eastern sector of the zone.
</P>
<P>
On Wednesday, one Hezbollah gunman was killed in the Ali Tahr
hill range in the eastern sector. In a separate incident late
Wednesday night, Hezbollah forces fired Sagger missiles at two
Israeli tanks in the Barasheet area in the western sector,
damaging one tank but causing no Israeli casualties. Israel
responded with heavy shelling of Hezbollah targets.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Israel Army has instructed troops in south Lebanon
to take precautions against possible kidnaping plot by the
Popular Front for the Liberation of Palestine, a Syria-based
anti-Israeli Palestinian group.
</P>
<P>
Speaking in Washington Thursday, Israeli Coordinator on
Lebanon Uri Lubrani claimed that Iran had shipped large
quantities of weapons to Hezbollah via Syria in the past four
months.
</P>
<P>
He said the shipments may include some more advanced weapons,
such as long-range Katyusha rockets capable of reaching Israel's
Haifa port in the north.
</P>
<P>
Israel has occupied the 15-kilometer wide self-proclaimed
south Lebanon security zone since 1985 under the excuse of
protecting security of its north. The Hezbollah forces have been
fighting a vigorous battle to liberate the zone from the Israeli
occupation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
