<HEADLINE> ASEAN Defense Officials to Meet in Manila </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, May 16 (Xinhua) -- Military and defense officials from
members of the Association of Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN) will
start a five-day meeting here next Monday to discuss "the
political and security implications of an expanded ASEAN."
</P>
<P>
A sequel to the ASEAN Defense Technology Exchange (ADTEX)
conference in 1995, ADTEX '97 "hopes to contribute to the thrust
of the ASEAN Regional Forum to foster confidence building measures
among its members," said a statement issued here today by the
ADTEX Secretariat.
</P>
<P>
At the meeting, the statement said, the participants will
tackle regional security and development issues and articulate
specific insights and perspectives.
</P>
<P>
"The objective of direct and meaningful communication among
military professionals has inspired the formation of ADTEX whose
vision is to be part of the active and reinforcing organizations
advocating and working for peace in Asia," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
"The presumption is that tension is diffused when there is an
unhampered and a continuing communication among those who operate
and manage the ASEAN defense forces," it said.
</P>
<P>
Ex-chiefs of defense forces will also attend part of the
meeting to enhance understanding of each member's view of ASEAN
security issues, according to the ADTEX secretariat.
</P>
<P>
ASEAN currently groups Brunei, Indonesia, Malaysia, the
Philippines, Singapore, Thailand and Vietnam.  
</P>
