coordinator Dennis Ross, which was to have taken place
Thursday night, according to a report of the state-run Israel
Radio.
</P>
<P>
The report quoted an announcement released by the Arafat's
Office, as saying that the Palestinian leader was too busy.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, a planned meeting for today between the heads of
the Israeli General Security Service and Palestinian Preventive
Security Service has also been canceled.
</P>
<P>
The meeting was to take place at the U.S. Embassy in Tel
Aviv. The two sides met at the embassy last week.
</P>
<P>
Saeb Erekat, chief Palestinian negotiator, told reporters
Thursday that what is needed is a freeze of the Jewish
settlements in the occupied Palestinian territories, and is,
particularly, an end of the construction of the settlement at
Har Homa in East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
Erekat said bitterly that the Palestinians had not heard this
from Mr. Ross and that, in effect, the settlement will
continue.
</P>
<P>
Ross, who arrived in the region last week, has shuttled
between Israeli and Palestinian leaders in an attempt to
revive the peace talks that have broken off for two months
since March. But his mediation turned out to be a failure.
</P>
<P>
Ross also visited Cairo and Amman. He is leaving for
Washington later today. 
