<HEADLINE> Cause of Indonesia's Ill-Fated Aircraft Still </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, May 16 (Xinhua) -- The flight recorder (black box) of
the Indonesia's Merpati Nusantara Airlines (MNA) aircraft which
crashed in Tanjung Pandan, South Sumatera, on April 19, 1997, has
been returned to Indonesia, but the cause of the mishap was still
unknown.
</P>
<P>
"We have received it from Australia about two weeks ago, and
the Aircraft Accident Investigation Committee is still studying
the case in their regular meetings, while the final outcome is
still unknown," MNA spokesman Prasetyo Wisaksono said here today.
</P>
<P>
The ill-fated ATP-type aircraft flying from Jakarta to Tanjung
Pandan on April 19, went down when about to land at Buluh Tumbang
airport in Tanjung Pandan.
</P>
<P>
Built by British Aerospace, the plane had 48 people on board,
and 15 people, including its crew of three, were killed in the
accident.
</P>
<P>
Prasetyo said the committee meeting will also provide the
government with inputs on the condition of MNA's grounded ATPs.
</P>
<P>
"The committee will report the outcome of the investigation to
the government, and it would then be up to the government whether
or not the ATPs would remain grounded," he said.
</P>
<P>
On April 21, Transportation Minister Haryanto Dhanutirto
ordered the grounding of Merpati's all ATPs until the cause of the
accident has been established.  
</P>
</TEXT>
