<HEADLINE> U.S., DPRK Agree to Excavate Remains of Missing American </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, May 15 (Xinhua) -- The United States and the
Democratic People's Republic of Korea (DPRK) have agreed to
jointly search for remains of American servicemen missing in the
Korean War, the Pentagon said today.
</P>
<P>
The two countries will conduct three joint recovery operations
this year and the first one is expected to begin within a month,
Pentagon spokesman Larry Greer said.
</P>
<P>
The United States has agreed to pay the DPRK 105,000
U.S. dollars in expenses for each joint excavation, he said.
</P>
<P>
The DPRK agreed to give U.S. investigators access to the
Fatherland Liberation War Museum in Pyongyang for information on
missing U.S. servicemen, Greer said.
</P>
<P>
The agreement was reached on Wednesday after five days of talks
between the two sides in New York last week.
</P>
<P>
More than 8,100 Americans are still listed as missing from the
Korean War, and as many as 4,000 remains potentially could be
recovered, Greer said.
</P>
<P>
But the spokesman said further talks are needed to agree on the
exact sites to be excavated. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
