<HEADLINE> Cuba Welcomes Planned Visit by Spanish Royalty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAVANA, May 15 (Xinhua) -- After a road accident two months ago
that strained Cuban-Spanish relations, Cuba welcomes a planned
visit by Spanish King Juan Carlos I and Queen Dona Sofia, the Foreign
Ministry said today.
</P>
<P>
Cuba always hopes to maintain normal ties with its former
metropolis and to strengthen them, although there are highs and
lows occurring in the process, said Cuban Foreign Ministry
spokeswoman Marianela Ferriol.
</P>
<P>
A Spanish newspaper today quoted Spanish Foreign Minister Abel
Matutes as saying the royal couple was planning a visit to the
Caribbean island. But Matutes did not give a date.
</P>
<P>
Relations had soured when a Spanish tourist was detained by
Cuban police in March after a traffic accident. He was released
after the Spanish embassy paid the bail.
</P>
<P>
While hailing the royal visit, Ferriol also criticized the
Spanish parliament decision to deprive Cuba of its right as a full
member to attend the Spanish parliamentary summit later this month
in Madrid.
</P>
<P>
The Cuban parliament was invited only as an observer this year,
despite its previous participations as a formal member.
</P>
<P>
Ferriol said that Cuban Parliament President Ricardo Alarcon
rejected such an attitude.
</P>
<P>
Cuban-Spanish ties began to cool after the Spanish Prime
Minister Jose Maria Aznar took office in May, 1996. It worsened
last November when Havana rejected the ambassador to Cuba, Jose
Coderch, who had said his embassy would be open to opponents of
the Cuban government.
</P>
<P>
Spain has not named a new ambassador to Cuba since then.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
