<DOCNO> XIE19970516.0246 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Hard, Positive Step Towards </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, May 16 (Xinhua) -- The prime ministers of Pakistan
and India have taken a hard, yet positive step towards
normalization of relations between the two South Asian nations
who fought three wars in the past 50 years.
</P>
<P>
Pakistani Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif and his Indian
counterpart Inder Kumar Gujril had a meeting this week in Male,
capital of the Maldives, at the ninth Summit of the South Asian
Association for Regional Cooperation and discussed a wide range of
issues between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
This is the first meeting between the top executives of the two
countries since April 1993.
</P>
<P>
In their 90-minute talks the two leaders agreed to release
civil prisoners stranded in both countries and to establish a hot
line between them to have a consistent contact.
</P>
<P>
They also agreed to set up working groups aimed at resolving
all outstanding issues including the Kashmir issue and continue
the foreign secretary-level talks.
</P>
<P>
Sharif said the meeting was "constructive and meaningful,"
while Gujril termed it as "very warm."
</P>
<P>
The meeting, which broke the deadlock in relations between the
two South Asian neighbors, is widely hailed as a "breakthrough"
and a new start in the process of normalization of bilateral
relations.
</P>
<P>
The most encouraging thing is that the two leaders had their
first face-to-face meeting and expressed their desire to resolve
all outstanding issues between the two countries through dialogue.
</P>
<P>
Relations between the two sub-continental nations have long
been abnormal and sometimes strained since they gained
independence in 1947 mainly due to the Kashmir issue on which the
two still stick to their respective positions.
</P>
<P>
The three wars in 1947, 1965 and 1971, the first two caused by
the Kashmir issue, deteriorated the Pak-Indian relations and made
the two countries keeping their defense expenditures escalating.
</P>
<P>
The huge defense expenditures hindered greatly the
socio-economic development of the two countries where most people
are still living under the poverty line.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan and India, the two biggest countries in the region who
shared the same historical past, are now facing the same tasks to
develop the economy and improve the living standard of the
peoples.
</P>
<P>
Sharif and Gujril, who assumed the premiership respectively in
February and April this year, have vowed to try their best to
improve the bilateral relations.
</P>
<P>
At the end of March, the two countries resumed the foreign
secretary-level talks which had been suspended for more than three
years.
</P>
<P>
Analysts here believe that though the Male meeting has achieved
some positive results, it is unrealistic to predict that relations
between Pakistan and India will be normalized over night.
</P>
<P>
There are still many obstacles, the Kashmir issue in
particular, on the way towards the establishment of good
neighborly relations between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Both Pakistan and India, in fact, have been victims of the old
colonialism. There is no reason for them to be hostile to each
other today when the rest of the world has focused on seeking
cooperation for economic development.
</P>
<P>
Analysts here believe that the normalization of the Pak-Indian
relations is of great importance to peace, stability and
development of the South Asian region. Establishing a
good-neighborly relationship is in the interests of the two
peoples.
</P>
<P>
If Pakistan and India can abandon all previous ill will and
seek common ground while reserving differences, they will be able
to resolve all outstanding issues on the basis of peaceful
consultation and establish good-neighborly and friendly
relationship towards the future.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970516.0247 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-16 </DATE_TIME>
