<P>
BANGKOK, May 16 (Xinhua) -- The Thai government has approved a
budget of 126.61 million baht (5.06 million US dollars) to help
exporters obtain raw materials at a lower cost as part of its plan
to promote exports, according to Commerce Ministry officials.
</P>
<P>
The budget, covering 1998 to 2001, will help exporters identify
new sources of raw materials. In addition, the money will be used
to help business cut production costs.
</P>
<P>
Wisitsee Chintana, senior official of the Commerce Ministry,
said the Commerce Ministry will have a meeting with exporters on
May 21 to identify ways to maximize the budget.
</P>
<P>
Thai commercial officers overseas will be in charge of the
project. Wisitsee said local producers of animal feed, fishmeal,
maize, canned sea food, textiles, jewelry and electrical
appliances and electronics are facing an inadequate supply of raw
materials.
</P>
<P>
The plan is in line with the 8th national economic and social
development plan, which aims to turn Thailand into a regional
trade center by obtaining raw materials from cheaper sources.
</P>
</TEXT>
