<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka's Tamil Rebels Desperate to Meet British PM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, May 16 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lankan Liberation Tigers of
Tamil Eelam (LTTE) is making a desperate attempt to meet British
Prime Minister Tony Blair to win legal recognition and seek his
assistance for their cause, according to Defense Ministry sources
here.
</P>
<P>
LTTE organizations in London and Birmingham have contacted
several Labour Party members of parliament in a bid to win
sympathy from the new British government, the sources quoted
reports reaching here today as saying.
</P>
<P>
The MPs have, however, indicated to the LTTE representatives
that their stand on terrorism was very clear and they would not
support any terrorism in any country.
</P>
<P>
Reports from London also state that the LTTE is making attempts
to raise funds for the LTTE and collect other goods and medicines
and send them to Sri Lanka for the LTTE through diplomatic
channels.
</P>
<P>
The LTTE's foreign resources have dried up and now they are
confined to the jungles in Sri Lanka. The civil population, which
the tigers had hitherto used as a human shield, has now deserted
them. 
</P>
</TEXT>
