<HEADLINE> Thai PM Leaves for Myanmar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, May 16 (Xinhua) -- Thai Prime Minister Chavalit
Yongchaiyudh left for Myanmar today on a two-day official visit.
</P>
<P>
Chavalit is expected to express his strong support for Thai
investors' activities in Myanmar and to urge Myanmar to facilitate
the entry of Thai investors into the country, according to Thai
Foreign Ministry sources.
</P>
<P>
He is also expected to express Thailand's support for Myanmar's
membership in ASEAN and may offer to help improve a road from the
newly-completed Thai-Myanmar border bridge to Yangon.
</P>
<P>
Apart from witnessing the signing of a border-crossing
agreement, Chavalit is expected to explore the possibility of the
two countries cooperating in the development of several deep-sea
ports in southern Myanmar, which could help shorten routes for
Europe-bound shipments of Thai products.
</P>
<P>
The Thai prime minister will also seek cooperation from the
Myanmar side to curb illegal Myanmar immigrants to enter Thailand,
now estimated to be about 700,000.
</P>
<P>
Included in the prime minister's entourage are presidents of
the Federation of Thai industries, the Board of Trade and the Thai
Bankers Association.  
</P>
