<DOCNO> XIE19970516.0266 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Brazil Hails U.S. Offer of Trade Barrier Cut </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELO HORIZONTE, Brazil, May 15 (Xinhua) -- Brazilian Foreign
Minister Luiz Felipe Lampreia today welcomed a United States
decision to send a mission to Brazil soon to study the possibility
of reducing U.S. trade barriers to Brazilian exports.
</P>
<P>
Calling it "a concrete step in the right direction," Lampreia
said: "It is a positive gesture that should make negotiations
easier."
</P>
<P>
At a meeting with Lampreia and Brazilian Industry and Commerce
Minister Francisco Dornelles, U.S. Commerce Secretary William
Daley said his country is willing to stop collecting compensatory
customs tariffs for Brazilian goods, including oranges and steel
products.
</P>
<P>
Dornelles said Daley also offered to review U.S. anti-dumping
procedures which, Brazil says, hurts the exports of Brazil's most
competitive products, including steel, orange juice, shoes and
textiles.
</P>
<P>
However, some Brazilians doubt U.S. sincerity to make good the
promise. A Brazilian diplomat said under anonymity that the offer
of removing trade barriers was "an insufficient gesture."
</P>
<P>
"We are tired of this kind of hypocrisy, because the same thing
was said in March by the U.S. secretary of commerce," he said.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. offer came just prior to the Third Trade Minister
Meeting of the Free Trade Area of Americas (FTAA), which is to
decide the timing of negotiations to create the hemispherical free
trade zone from Alaska to Argentina.
</P>
<P>
The United States and Brazil are divided over the speed of
setting up a pan-American free trade area. The United States wants
to drop all tariffs and barriers as soon as possible, while
Brazil, leading the booming subregional trade bloc of the Southern
American Common Market (Mercosur), insists on a step-by-step
integration, putting off tariff cuts to later.
</P>
<P>
Trade ministers from 34 countries of the Western Hemisphere are
meeting at Belo Horizonte to discuss the future free trade area,
which would contain 52 percent of the world trade.
</P>
<P>
Brazil steel and steel product exports to the United States
could increase by a third, going from the present 1.5 billion
U.S. dollars to two billion dollars, once U.S. trade barriers are
lifted. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
