<HEADLINE> Chilean Defense Minister Visits Argentina </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES, May 15 (Xinhua) -- Chilean Defense Minister
Edmundo Perez Yoma arrived here today for a two-day visit to
Argentina.
</P>
<P>
Perez told a joint press conference with his Argentine
counterpart, Jorge Dominguez, in the Metropolitan Airport, that
his country's relations with Argentina are "excellent," and the
understanding of the two countries on defense matters has reached
a "noticeable" level.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that there is a transparency in the bilateral
relations that few Latin American countries have, adding Chile has
informed Argentina about its acquisition of planes and submarines
for its armed forces.
</P>
<P>
He announced Chile has bought from France two conventional
submarines, which will be delivered by the year 2005.
</P>
<P>
Agreeing with Perez that the relations between the two
countries are excellent, Dominguez said: "We know the intentions
of Chile and we do not believe that there is an arms race in the
region."
</P>
<P>
It is believed that Perez's visit is designed to show Chile's
desire for cooperation with Argentina.
</P>
<P>
The two countries have had a string of border disputes and
differences in the demarcation over Antarctic "Ice Fields" in
their southern border still exist, though a protocol signed last
December is waiting for their parliamentary rulings.
</P>
<P>
Relations between the two sides, however, have been improved
recently. 
</P>
</TEXT>
