<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Denies Leaving Toxic Wastes in Philippines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, May 16 (Xinhua) -- The United States has denied the
fact that its troops left behind hundreds of tons of toxic wastes
when they pulled out of the Clark Air Base in the northern
Philippines in 1991.
</P>
<P>
Today's local press quoted US Embassy Press Attache Bruce Byers
as saying that it has never been ascertained that the former US
air base was the source of toxic wastes.
</P>
<P>
Byers said the U.S. government has "no legal authority" to
clean up the air base after it relinquished its authority to the
Philippine government in 1991.
</P>
<P>
"There may be toxic wastes in Clark and Subic, but these may
not have to do with the US," Byers said in a press briefing on
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
But environmentalists insisted that the US presence was the
source of the hazardous wastes, saying some 17,000 families living
at Clark complained of gastrointestinal disorder and skin rashes.
</P>
<P>
These diseases, the environmentalists said, are believed linked
to their use of contaminated water from some wells that had been
dug up at the former U.S. air base, which has been built into an
economic zone.
</P>
<P>
They added that military facilities and operations generate
large quantities of hazardous wastes from production, testing,
cleaning, maintenance and extensive use of weapons and explosives.
</P>
<P>
The US withdrew troops from Clark, Subic and other four
military bases after the Philippine Senate refused the extension
of their military base agreements.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970516.0274 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bonn Plans Further Privatization to Ease Budget Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, May 15 (Xinhua) -- German Finance Minister Theo Waigel
said today that he is planning to speed up the privatization of
the German telecommunications flag-carrier Deutsche Telecom, and
to revalue gold reserves held by the central bank in a bid to fill
the huge gap that has emerged in the country's budget.
</P>
<P>
Waigel said that the fund-raising concept had already been
approved by lawmakers of Chancellor Helmut Kohl's Christian
Democratic Union (CDU) and its Bavarian sister party Christian
Social Union (CSU).
</P>
<P>
Germany was confronted with a budget crisis Thursday when a tax
estimate group consisted of both government and independent
experts revealed that the country's federal, state and community
governments' tax revenues this year would be 18 billion German
marks (10.65 billion U.S. dollars) less than earlier estimated.
</P>
<P>
This announcement and the strong reactions afterwards from the
political parties have unleashed huge pressure on the government
to find urgent financial measures to defuse the crisis.
</P>
<P>
The Telecom privatization, which Waigel is considering to speed
up, was launched in November last year. But the government now
still holds 75 percent of its shares and pledged earlier that it
would not dispose of any of them before the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
By selling off part of the Telecom stake it still holds, the
government would avoid the embarrassment of having to return to
parliament to seek an increase in its public borrowings for the
year, experts said.
</P>
<P>
Forced by the little leeway left for the government to ease the
fiscal burden, Waigel Thursday also rushed to Frankfurt to consult
Germany's central bank, the Bundesbank, about an revaluation of its
gold reserves.
</P>
<P>
For historical reasons, Germany's gold reserves are undervalued
at about 14 billion marks (8.3 billion dollars), which should be
57 billion marks (33.7 billion dollars) under current market value.
</P>
<P>
Economists said revaluing the gold reserves would boost the
Bundesbank's profits and consequently generate additional revenue
for the national accounts.
</P>
<P>
German media reported there are speculations that the Bonn
government might also consider to increase indirect taxes, such as
petrol tax, as an additional fund-raising measure. At least Waigel
has left that option open on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
But tax hikes was strongly opposed by the Free Democratic Party
(FDP), the junior partner in Germany's ruling coalition.
</P>
<P>
Otte Solms, Chairman of the FDP parliamentary group said
Thursday evening in Bonn that raising taxes would be the worst
option for the economy and the job market.
</P>
<P>
Observers pointed out that with less than 12 months left before
the European Union (EU) decides which state can join its planned
single currency, the Euro. Germany's current budget crisis raised
renewed doubt about its ability to make the grade for qualifying
for the Euro as a founding member on January 1, 1999. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
