<HEADLINE> 2 States Impose Ban on Victorian Apples, Pears </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, May 16 (Xinhua) -- Two states in Australia have
banned Victorian apples and pears, heading a wave of anxiety over
Australia's first fireblight outbreak, local newspaper reports
said.
</P>
<P>
The states of Tasmania and Western Australia had banned pears,
apples and plant material from the state of Victoria in response
to the outbreak.
</P>
<P>
Tens of millions of dollars worth of apple and pear production
and hundreds of rural jobs hinge on the successful containment of
the disease, which is harmless to humans, but devastating to
fruit-tree productivity.
</P>
<P>
The disease was detected in Melbourne by Chris Hale, a visiting
fireblight expert with the Agriculture Ministry of New Zealand,
the Melbourne-based newspaper the Age reported today.
</P>
<P>
The disease spread widely in New Zealand and Australia has
banned the imports of apples from New Zealand.
</P>
<P>
After surveys of plants in all public parks and gardens in the
city, the disease had still been detected in only two plants in
the gardens, state Agriculture Minister Pat McNamara said.
</P>
<P>
About 35 plant experts, quarantine officials and industry
representatives met in the city yesterday to develop a strategy to
eradicate the disease.
</P>
<P>
The meeting resolved to try to eliminate the disease, which
impairs apple and pear production throughout the world, but which
remains undetected in Australia's key fruit-growing areas.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
