<HEADLINE> Several Hurt in Police Clash With Students </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAVANA, May 15 (Xinhua) -- Police today clashed with students
who occupied a school in the Haitian capital of Port-au-Prince and
hurt several people, reports said.
</P>
<P>
Police fired tear gas and live bullets in the air. At least two
people were reported to have received bullet wounds, and several
others were beaten or wounded by rocks.
</P>
<P>
The Reuters news agency quoted sources in the General Hospital
as saying that five people were seriously wounded, but there were
no reports of fatalities.
</P>
<P>
The riot began when about 300 students occupied the Petion
School which had been closed since Monday after teachers walked
out in protest against pay delays.
</P>
<P>
The students threw rocks, injuring bystanders. Riot police
arrived on the scene and fired tear gas and students responded by
hurling fuel bombs, the agency said.
</P>
<P>
Police broke into the school to arrest students and several
demonstrators were badly beaten and at least two shot, said
witnesses.
</P>
<P>
Police withdrew but the unrest flared up as rioters rampaged
through downtown streets, setting ablaze buildings, homes and cars.
</P>
<P>
There is widespread discontent in this Caribbean nation with a
government privatization program and austerity measures promoted
by the International Monetary Fund and other foreign donors.
</P>
<P>
Grassroots organizations opposed to President Rene Preval's
policies have held a series of protest strikes and threatened to
use violence to enforce their message.
</P>
<P>
Preval took power in February 1996 after winning an election
with the backing of Jean-Bertrand Aristide.
</P>
<P>
Aristide was deposed by a coup in 1991 and restored after three
years in exile by a United States-led military invasion which
ousted the military regime. 
</P>
</TEXT>
