<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Tension Heightens in NZ Parliament </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, May 16 (Xinhua) -- Tension in the New Zealand
parliament has heightened between the opposition and Deputy Prime
Minister Winston Peters over the issue of he allegedly assaulting
a National backbencher more than two months ago.
</P>
<P>
The incident took place on March 5 night outside the debating
chamber, when Peters reportedly had a scuffle with John Banks, a
backbench MP of the National Party.
</P>
<P>
The parliament privileges committee ruled on Wednesday that
Peters' conduct on that night was "unbecoming" and invited him to
apologize to Parliament for the unacceptable behavior.
</P>
<P>
However, Peters reiterated this morning his determination not
to apologize after he refused to do so yesterday.
</P>
<P>
He said he never knew what he was charged with by the
committee, and likened the situation to a person charged with
forgery being convicted of murder.
</P>
<P>
In his speech in parliament yesterday, Peters angrily attacked
the committee's decision.
</P>
<P>
"Had there been a fair charge formulated, and I got a fair
hearing on that, and if I was then found guilty, I would
apologize. I was not, and therefore I will not," he said.
</P>
<P>
He stated that the committee had dismissed the allegation that
he was in contempt of parliament, and had no jurisdiction to rule
on the allegation of assault.
</P>
<P>
The allegation was made by Alliance leader Jim Anderton, who
was a witness at the scene of the scuffle.
</P>
<P>
Referring to Anderton, Peters said, "if you think I'm going to
cower in front of this House while you made false statements then
you are wrong."
</P>
<P>
He said he also intends to sue Labour deputy leader Machael
Cullen for defamation over his claim Peters had been drunk at the
time of the alleged assault. Peters has been insisting all along
that he was sober at that time.
</P>
<P>
However, the scuffle issue created by Peters, leader of the New
Zealand First party, has made his coalition partner, the National
Party, uneasy.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Jim Bolger tried to distance himself yesterday
from Peters' refusal to apologize by staying away when Peters took
the defiant stand in parliament.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman for Bolger said the prime minister was in his
office at the time of debate, busy writing speeches for National
Party conferences at the weekend.
</P>
<P>
But privately, some National MPs said they were surprised by
Peters' refusal, and it had put further pressure on the Coalition
relationship.
</P>
<P>
A recent opinion poll showed a decline in the support of the
coalition. Observers believe some improper conducts of NZ First
MPs are partly responsible for the fall.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
