<HEADLINE> Arrested Ecuadorean Soldiers Handed Back </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
QUITO, May 15 (Xinhua) -- Ecuador said that the seven soldiers,
who were arrested Wednesday by Peru for crossing into a disputed
border zone, were handed back to Ecuador today, putting an end to
the border incident.
</P>
<P>
Peru said a heavily armed Ecuadorean patrol was arrested on
Wednesday while planting mines six kilometers inside Peru's
territory.
</P>
<P>
Ecuador's Defense Ministry issued a communique, saying the
seven soldiers were illegally arrested while carrying out normal
activities and routine patrols in the Paquisha Alto sector of the
disputed frontier.
</P>
<P>
But the head of the Ecuador's armed forces, General Paco
Moncayo, also admitted that the patrol may have strayed into the
Peruvian territory.
</P>
<P>
The arrests came as negotiators from Lima and Quito began a
second round of talks in the Brazilian capital, Brasilia, on a
permanent solution to the decades-old border dispute.
</P>
<P>
The two nations had bloody clashes in the border area in
January, 1995. Dozens of soldiers were killed and hundreds injured
on both sides before a ceasefire agreement was reached in March,
1995.
</P>
<P>
Both Peru and Ecuador described the Wednesday arrest as a
border incident, saying there was no fighting between the two
armies and no one was hurt.
</P>
<P>
Moncayo said the Ecuadorean authorities had ordered an
investigation, while Peru's acting Foreign Minister Jorge Gonzalez
Izquierdo said he was confident the peace dialogue would stay on
track despite the incident. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
