<HEADLINE> Russia: Opposition to NATO Expansion Unchanged </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, May 15 (Xinhua) -- Russian Foreign Minister Yevgeny
Primakov said here today that Moscow's opposition to NATO's
eastward expansion was unchanged.
</P>
<P>
Russia still opposed NATO's expansion as it had done before,
and considered the expansion a serious mistake, Primakov told
visiting U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan, who arrived here
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
He said that as Moscow was not a NATO member, it did not seek
veto on matters within the military alliance, but demanded equal
rights with NATO on decision-making over joint actions.
</P>
<P>
"Russia and NATO will have the right to discuss any questions
which they think are necessary to put forth for mutual
consideration" in the future Russia-NATO Council, the foreign
minister said.
</P>
<P>
Annan would meet with President Boris Yeltsin on Friday before
leaving Moscow. 
