<HEADLINE> Bulgaria President Calls Russian-NATO Deal 'Encouraging' </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SOFIA, May 15 (Xinhua) -- Bulgarian President Petar Stoyanov
said today he was pleased with the deal reached between Russia and
the North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO) on forging a
peaceful new relationship.
</P>
<P>
The agreement was announced in Moscow Wednesday after two hours
of tough negotiations between NATO Secretary General Javier Solana
and Russian Foreign Minister Yevgeny Primakov.
</P>
<P>
The deal, which is expected to be signed on May 27, is aimed at
placating Russia before NATO, a western military alliance,
recruits new members from former Soviet bloc countries in eastern
Europe, a move Russia has strongly opposed.
</P>
<P>
Stoyanov said the deal was encouraging news for these countries
which planned to join NATO.
</P>
<P>
It proved that Bulgaria's decision to join the alliance was
correct and timely, he said.
</P>
<P>
The Czech Republic, Poland and Hungary are expected to be among
the first group of eastern European countries to join NATO this
summer. 
</P>
</TEXT>
