<HEADLINE> World's Oldest Giant Panda on Last Legs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WUHAN, May 16 (Xinhua) -- She is blind and unable to eat
anything solid. Her owner is even ready to build a mausoleum and a
monument after its death.
</P>
<P>
"Dudu", at the age of 35, the world's oldest giant panda in
captivity and the most venerable age in its family, is struggling
against disease.
</P>
<P>
"She is too old to maintain good physical condition," said
keeper Chen Jun at the zoo in this capital of Central China's
Hubei Province. "She lost her eyesight due to keratitis. And
because she has lost most of her teeth, she hasn't eaten her
favorite food -- bamboo leaves -- for eight years."
</P>
<P>
"Dudu" recently refused to take porridge and milk and lost
weight rapidly. "Fortunately, she has almost recovered, thanks to
intensive treatment and care," Chen said.
</P>
<P>
The giant panda is one of the most endangered species on
earth. There are only some 1,000 of them left, most of them living
in west China's Sichuan, Gansu and Shaanxi provinces.
</P>
<P>
The life span of a panda is generally six to 20 years and no
panda older than 30 years had been reported before.
</P>
<P>
The female panda was captured and sent to the zoo in Chengdu,
Sichuan, in 1967. The panda, who moved to Wuhan in 1973, was once
mated but had no children. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
