<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Background: ABCs of Basic Law of Hong Kong SAR (85-86) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 16 (Xinhua) -- Following are the ABCs of the Basic
Law of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (85-86) in a
question-and-answer format:
</P>
<P>
Question: Will place names reflecting colonial rule be changed
after 1997?
</P>
<P>
Answer: More than 150 years of British colonial rule have, in
varying degrees, left marks of such a rule in many aspects of Hong
Kong life.
</P>
<P>
This is reflected in the names of some streets, parks, buildings
and public welfare institutions, such as Victoria Harbor, Kennedy
Town and Queen's Road.
</P>
<P>
The government of the Hong Kong SAR will decide whether or not
to change such names after 1997 in accordance with the will of
Hong Kong people. The Basic Law contains no specific provisions
in this regard.
</P>
<P>
Question: Will horse races continue in Hong Kong after 1997?
</P>
<P>
Answer: Of total betting money in Hong Kong's horse races, 81.9
percent is paid to winners, 7.4 percent to the Jockey Club as
commission, and the remaining 10.7 percent to the government as a
lottery tax with most of this tax being used for charitable
services.
</P>
<P>
Horse racing has become an inseparable part of the daily life
of many residents. It is difficult for outsiders to understand
Hong Kong people's fondness for horse racing. It is, therefore,
quite natural for Hong Kong residents to be concerned about its
continued existence after 1997.
</P>
<P>
There is in fact no cause for any worries in this regard. The
policy of "one country, two systems" will be applied in Hong Kong
after 1997, and the region's current social system and lifestyle
will remain unchanged for 50 years.
</P>
<P>
The Basic Law provides legal protection for the rights and
freedom of Hong Kong people. Horse racing will continue.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970516.0304 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-16 </DATE_TIME>
