<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Attorney General Seeks Death Penalty in Unabomber Case </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, May 15 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Attorney General Janet Reno
today requested the death penalty for Unabomber suspect Theodore
Kaczynski.
</P>
<P>
Reno ordered prosecutors to seek the death penalty on grounds
that Kaczynski allegedly killed two men with "planning and
premeditation," lacks remorse and still presents a danger to the
lives of others.
</P>
<P>
The 54-year-old former mathematics professor has pleaded
innocent to federal charges in Sacramento, California, and Newark,
New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
Last year, Kaczynski's younger brother, David, and mother,
Wanda, tipped the FBI, ending the government's unsuccessful
18-year, nationwide manhunt for the Unabomber.
</P>
<P>
Kaczynski's family argued to Justice officials that other
families would be reluctant to turn in relatives if death were the
result in this case.
</P>
<P>
But Reno granted prosecutors' requests to seek the death
penalty in the case.
</P>
<P>
Prosecutors told federal courts in Sacramento and Newark that
death is warranted because Kaczynski intended to kill and harm
people and has little "potential for rehabilitation."
</P>
<P>
Prosecutors said Kaczynski killed three people and injured 23
others in 16 bombings.
</P>
<P>
Kaczynski was arrested by the FBI on April 3, 1996, at his
remote cabin near Lincoln, Montana. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
