<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Blair Presses on With Scottish, Welsh Assembly Plans </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, May 15 (Xinhua) -- Shortly after announcing a bill to
allow for referendums on giving Scotland and Wales their own
parliaments, British Prime Minister Tony Blair showed his
determination to push through the plans today.
</P>
<P>
Labor government parliamentary business manager Ann Taylor
announced that the first discussion of the devolution to Scotland
and Wales by MPs would take place next Tuesday and Wednesday in
the House of Commons, local reports said.
</P>
<P>
The Labor government plans a Scottish parliament with a limited
ability to vary taxes in Edinburgh, and a rather less powerful
Welsh Senedd (senate) in Cardiff to take decisions on local
issues.
</P>
<P>
The referendum is expected to be held in September if the bill
has completed its stages in both the Commons and the Lords by the
end of July, which would be the most radical constitutional
reforms in Scotland and Wales for 300 years.
</P>
<P>
However, the opposition Conservatives are against the bill,
arguing that setting up these parliaments could finally lead to
the break-up of Britain. But the Conservatives seemed unable to
obstruct the devolution proposals because they have only 165 seats
in the lower house while the Labor occupies 419 seats.
</P>
<P>
In 1978, the last Labor government also offered Scotland and
Wales their own parliaments, but the plan was dropped after both
regions showed little interest in such referendums. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970516.0308 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> German Central Bank Reports Growing Gap Between Rich, Poor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, May 15 (Xinhua) -- Germany's central bank today reported
a widening income gap within the German society, with the rich
becoming richer and the poor even poorer.
</P>
<P>
In its monthly report for May issued today, the central bank,
known as the Bundesbank, noted that while the income of the
country's wage earners and those receiving social welfare benefits
declined, the earnings from corporate activities and on capital
appreciation increased.
</P>
<P>
In total, Germany's private wealth is continuing to grow, up
nearly 300 billion marks (178 billion U.S. dollars) in 1996 to a
new record of almost 5 trillion marks (3 trillion dollars), the
Bundesbank said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Germany's household debts also increased last year
to 1.72 trillion marks (1.02 trillion dollars) from 1.60 trillion
marks (946 million dollars) in 1995. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970516.0309 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US 30-Year Mortgage Declines Below 8 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, May 15 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. Federal Home Loan
Mortgage Corp. (Freddie Mac) reported today that the average rate
for a 30-year fixed-rate mortgage remains below the level of 8
percent.
</P>
<P>
Freddie Mac said that the average rate for the popular
home-lending tool for the week ending May 16 stands at 7.91
percent, down from last week's 7.94 percent.
</P>
<P>
The 30-year average mortgage rate jumped above 8 percent for
the first time since October after the U.S. Federal Reserve (Fed)
raised interest rates on March 25 and stayed above that mark until
the week ending May 8.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the average rate for a 15-year fixed-rate mortgage
also fell, dipping to 7.44 percent from 7.47 percent in the
previous week. The rate was 7.53 percent two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. Fed is set to meet again next week to discuss monetary
policy. Analysts remain divided over whether the central bank will
tighten rates further. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
