<DOCNO> XIE19970516.0310 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dow Surpasses 7,300 Mark </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, May 15 (Xinhua) -- New York stocks posted a late
advance today, boosting the Dow Jones industrial average and other
market measures to new highs, amid conflicting economic data.
</P>
<P>
The Dow gained 47.39 points to 7,333.55, beating Monday's
record finish at 7,292.75 and surpassing the 7,300 mark for the
first time.
</P>
<P>
Also setting new highs were the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock
list, up 5.84 to 841.88, and the New York Stock Exchange composite
index, up 2.05 to 437.65.
</P>
<P>
The Nasdaq composite index rose 18.07 to 1,353.62, and the
American Stock Exchange composite index rose 1.50 to 583.47.
</P>
<P>
Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a 10-to-9 margin on
the New York Stock Exchange, with NYSE volume totaling 458.14
million shares as against 498.77 million in the previous session.
</P>
<P>
The Labor Department reported that consumer prices, excluding
the volatile food and energy sectors, rose 0.3 percent in April,
slightly more than expected and the largest increase since
September.
</P>
<P>
In a separate reading that indicated continued upward pressure
on employment costs, the department also reported that first-time
claims for unemployment benefits fell 31,000 last week to 319,000,
a three-week low.
</P>
<P>
But bonds rebounded later in the morning after two subsequent
reports indicated that manufacturing activity is slowing.
</P>
<P>
In one report, the Federal Reserve reported that American
industry was operating at 83.4 percent of its capacity in April,
down from 83.7 percent in March.
</P>
<P>
By late afternoon, the long-bond yield fell slightly below late
today's 6.88 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
