<HEADLINE> Mandela, Kabila Ends Talks on Zairean Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, May 15 (Xinhua) -- South African President
Nelson Mandela said today that Zaire's embattled President Mobutu
Sese Seko and rebel leader Laurent Kabila are considering his
peace plan.
</P>
<P>
"Matter are going to plan," Mandela, a major mediator of the
Zairean crisis told a press conference at the end of his
two-and-a-half hour talks with Kabila in Cape Town. "We are
confident we are making progress," he said.
</P>
<P>
Kabila told the press conference: "We shall wait until Monday
to receive another answer from the Mobutu side."
</P>
<P>
Kabila would further study the two-page Zairean peace plan
prepared by Mandela. The plan has also been made available to
Mobutu, according South African officials.
</P>
<P>
Details of the peace plan were not yet known. But South
African officials indicated that it was a proposal of
power-sharing among Kabila's rebel forces, Mobutu's followers and
other opposition parties in the central African country.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, President Mandela canceled the second face-to-face
peace talks between Mobutu and Kabila originally scheduled today
in a South African ship off Congo's west African coast because
Kabila refused to attend, citing security reasons.
</P>
<P>
Then Mandela sent a jet plane to Kabinda, an enclave of
Angola, to fetch Kabila to Cape Town for an urgent consultation.
</P>
<P>
Kabila's rebel forces are still engaged in a fierce fighting
with Mobutu's presidential guards in Kengo, a strategic town 200
km east of Kinshasa, capital of Zaire. But Kabila's spokesman
said the rebel troops are approaching Kinshasa from other fronts.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
