<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Dollar Falls for Ninth Day Against yen </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, May 15 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. dollar lost all the gains
in 1997 against the yen up to today, dropping for the ninth
straight day despite comments by senior Japanese officials
suggesting the U.S. currency has fallen enough.
</P>
<P>
The dollar ended mixed in other foreign-exchange dealings.
</P>
<P>
The dollar fell as low as 115.85 yen in intraday dealings
before settling in New York at 116.10 yen, down from 117.20
Wednesday. It was the weakest since January 10 and left the dollar
barely above its 115.93-yen level at year-end 1996. Two weeks ago,
by contrast, the dollar hit a 4.5-year intraday high of 127.47
yen.
</P>
<P>
The dollar cost 1.6988 marks in New York, up from 1.6944. The
pound cost 1.6426 U.S. dollars, down from 1.6466 U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Traders continued to sell the dollar despite remarks by the top
officials in Japan's Finance Ministry suggesting they are now
content with the exchange-rate level.
</P>
<P>
Both Finance Minister Hiroshi Mitsuzuka and Vice Finance
Minister Tadashi Ogawa said the recent agreement by the Group of
Seven nations on foreign-exchange rates had been comprehended by
the foreign-exchange market.
</P>
<P>
Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with Wednesday:
1.4310 Swiss francs, down from 1.4363; 5.7110 French francs, up
from 5.7055; 1,672.00 Italian lire, up from 1,669.00; 1.3724
Canadian dollars, down from 1.3889. 
</P>
</TEXT>
